{[%evp 0,47,19,34,36,39,85,71,71,45,51,37,55,39,36,42,41,47,44,39,46,32,58,56,
56,23,28,9,29,10,113,41,30,23,29,27,23,21,-5,7,4,-7,-7,-84,-97,-110,-110,-120,
-99,-29997] A very nice game by Black showcasing the typical Rxc3-Rxf3! idea.} 
1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 a6 6. f3 e5 {The classical
Najdorf approach.} 7. Nb3 Be7 8. Be3 Be6 9. Qd2 h5 (9... b5 {In order to
successfuly play ...b5 we should complete our development first. Unfortunately,
That's not the case here and White is better. White can respond with Nd5 or a4.
} 10. a4 (10. Nd5 Bxd5 11. exd5) 10... b4 11. Nd5 Bxd5 12. exd5 O-O 13. Be2
Nbd7 14. O-O a5 15. Bb5 {White will win on the queenside. The pawns on a5-b4
are weak.}) 10. O-O-O Nbd7 11. Kb1 Rc8 12. g3 {Planning h3-g4.} (12. f4 b5 {
We shouldn't take on f4 yet.} 13. f5 Bc4 {with very strong counterplay for
Black.}) 12... b5 {Quite often in the Najdorf. Black is not in a hurry to 
castle.} 13. h3 (13. Qf2 Rxc3 {We can play this almost without thinking.} 14.
bxc3 Qc7 {Black has a huge advantage because we have all our pieces in the
attack. Especially after d6-d5 break.} 15. Qe1 O-O 16. Bd3 Rc8 17. h3 d5 (17...
Qxc3 {We should not trade queens in such positions.}) 18. exd5 Nxd5 19. Bd2
N7b6 {We have more pieces in the attack with a huge advantage.}) (13. f4 Rxc3 {
We should only sacrifice on c3 if we can double White's pawns.} 14. Qxc3 Nxe4
15. Qe1 {Black's compensation is not clear.}) 13... Nb6 14. Qf2 $2 Rxc3 $3 15.
Bxb6 (15. bxc3 {is really out of the question.} Na4) 15... Rxf3 $3 $17 {
is another very common idea.} 16. Qxf3 Qxb6 {Black has enough compensation as
he has enough material and White's b3-Knight is misplaced.} 17. Bg2 O-O 18. Qe2
a5 19. Bf3 a4 20. Nc1 Rc8 21. Bxh5 {White collected a pawn on h5 but he lost
time. His strategy should be to open lines.} a3 22. b3 Qc6 23. Bf3 d5 24. Qe3
0-1

