{[%evp 0,58,34,41,33,33,71,51,52,30,34,30,41,54,66,35,29,26,59,30,37,37,-13,-1,
-4,-16,-21,-8,-1,-26,89,80,68,38,49,81,63,-90,-119,-157,-151,-162,-227,-158,
-101,-385,-363,-363,-361,-361,-361,-361,-400,-426,-464,-496,-365,-387,-413,
-403,-402]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4
Nbd7 8. Qf3 Qc7 {The correct move order} (8... Be7 {is dubious because of} 9.
Bc4 Nb6 {The knight does not belong on b6.} 10. Bb3) 9. O-O-O (9. f5 e5 {
Is the correct move in most cases.} (9... Ne5 {is met by} 10. Qh3) 10. Nb3 b5 {
We have reached the perfect Najdorf setup.} 11. a3 Be7 12. Bd3 Bb7 13. O-O O-O)
9... b5 {After b5 our next move can be b4 or Rb8 or Bb7.} 10. Bd3 (10. Kb1 b4 {
is really good if White is forced to leave the center.} (10... Be7 11. Bd3 b4
$1 (11... Bb7 12. Rhe1)) 11. Nd5 {The only dangerous move. We are in concrete
grounds where the position is a big mess.} (11. Nce2 {means that White has
lost his opening advantage.} Bb7 12. Ng3 Nc5 (12... Be7) 13. Bxf6)) (10. a3 Rb8
{The typical motive against a3.} 11. Bd3 b4 12. axb4 Rxb4 13. Nde2 Be7) 10...
Bb7 11. Rhe1 {White is next planning Nd5 or Nf5.} Be7 12. a3 {According to
theory, 12.Qg3 is the best move.} Qb6 {Typical idea to plan b4.} 13. Nb3 (13.
Nde2 b4 14. axb4 Qxb4 {We can next create counterplay on the b-file.}) 13...
Rc8 $15 (13... e5 14. Kb1 (14. Qe2 Rc8 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. exd5) 14... Rc8 15. Nd5
) 14. Qh3 $2 (14. Ne2 e5 {Please be careful when we switch pawn structures.
Previously, with the Knight on c3 this wouldn't be ideal because of Nd5 ideas.
But now it is playable.} 15. Ng3 g6 {Strategically justified move!} 16. f5 a5 {
Intending a4 and b4.}) 14... Rxc3 15. bxc3 Qc7 $1 {The best move.} (15... e5 $1
{is also playable. Limiting Knight on b3 and stopping e5 ideas.} 16. fxe5 dxe5
$17) 16. Kb1 Nb6 17. f5 e5 18. Qg3 Na4 19. Bd2 O-O 20. Re3 d5 {with tremendous
play!} 21. Rde1 Qd6 22. Bf1 Nxe4 23. Rxe4 dxe4 24. Bc1 Rc8 25. Re3 Bd8 26. Qe1
Bg5 27. Rg3 Bxc1 28. Qxc1 Nxc3+ 29. Ka1 Bd5 0-1

