[SourceVersionDate "2023.10.06"]

{[%evp 0,58,19,31,72,53,68,72,57,39,38,30,64,43,95,29,22,16,31,25,20,16,6,-15,
-14,-30,-28,-73,-58,-52,-17,-47,11,-50,-77,-85,-77,-116,-131,-92,-96,-118,-75,
-75,-65,-66,-78,-228,-226,-226,-216,-216,-332,-484,-484,-484,-517,-537,-540,
-525,-502] Another great example about the two problematic knights on c3 and
b3 and how to chase them away at the best moment! This game is full of typical
Najdorf ideas so study it very well again and again and ideally memorize it !} 
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 (6... Nbd7 7. f3)
7. f4 Qb6 {The famous Poision pawn variation.} (7... Nbd7 8. Bc4 Qc7 9. Bxe6
fxe6 10. Nxe6 Qc4 11. f5) (7... h6 8. Bh4 Qb6) 8. Nb3 {White retreats with Nb3
in order to avoid the complication of the b2 sacrifice, but now his Nb3 is
absent from the action in the center! .... everything has a price!} (8. Qd2 {
mainline} Qxb2 9. Rb1 Qa3) (8. Qd3 {another common line.}) 8... Be7 (8... Qc7
9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Qf3 {This position is playable but risky.}) 9. Qf3 (9. e5 Qe3+
10. Qe2 Qxe2+ 11. Bxe2 dxe5 12. fxe5 Nfd7) 9... Nbd7 10. O-O-O Qc7 {Black goes
back but he has cleverly forced White's Knight to b3.} 11. Bd3 (11. Nd4 {
White is a tempo down compared to the theory.}) (11. g4 b5 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 (12...
Bxf6) 13. g5 Nd7 14. h4 (14. a3 Rb8 15. h4 b4 16. axb4 Rxb4 17. h5 Nc5 18. Nxc5
Qxc5 19. g6 O-O (19... Bf6) 20. h6 fxg6 21. hxg7 Kxg7 (21... Rf7) (21... Rxf4))
14... b4 (14... Bb7 $6 15. a3) 15. Ne2 a5 (15... Bb7)) 11... b5 (11... Rb8 12.
Rhe1 b5 13. e5 dxe5 14. fxe5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Qxe5 16. Bf4) 12. Rhe1 {Here are
some nice sample lines showing the typical ideas of these positions for both
colors! This is not theory just a logical human way of playing!} (12. a3 Rb8 {
is the right approach against a3. Please remember we are not forced to play
Bb7 immediately.} (12... Bb7 13. Rhe1 (13. g4 Rc8 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 (14... Nxf6 15.
g5 Nd7 16. h4 Qb6 17. Ne2 (17. Kb1 Rxc3 18. bxc3 Qc7 19. Kb2 (19. h5 Qxc3 (
19... O-O 20. g6 Bf6 (20... Nf6 21. gxf7+ Kxf7 (21... Rxf7)) 21. gxf7+ (21.
gxh7+ Kh8) 21... Rxf7)) 19... Nb6) 17... O-O (17... d5) 18. f5 (18. h5 a5 19.
g6 Bf6 (19... h6) 20. gxf7+ (20. gxh7+ Kh8) 20... Rxf7 21. Qh3 a4 22. Nd2 b4
23. Nc4 Bxb2+ 24. Kxb2 bxa3+) 18... exf5 19. Qxf5 Ne5)) 13... O-O (13... Rc8 $1
14. g4 Qb6 15. Ne2 (15. Kb1 Rxc3 16. bxc3 O-O 17. h3 (17. Bxf6 Nxf6 (17... Bxf6
18. g5 Bxc3) 18. g5 Nd7 19. h4 Qc7 (19... Rc8 20. h5 Qc7 21. g6 Nf6 (21... Bf6
22. gxf7+ Kxf7 23. f5 Qxc3 (23... exf5 24. Qxf5 Qxc3 25. Qxd7+ Kg8)) 22. gxf7+
Kxf7) 20. h5 Qxc3) 17... Qc7 18. Bf1 Rc8 19. Bg2 Nb6) 15... a5 16. Bxf6 Nxf6
17. g5 Nd7 18. h4 O-O 19. f5 exf5 20. Qxf5 Ne5 21. h5 a4 (21... g6) (21... Qe3+
) (21... b4 22. a4) 22. Nbd4 b4 23. axb4 Qxb4 24. g6 a3 25. gxh7+ (25. gxf7+
Rxf7) 25... Kh8) (13... h6 14. Bh4 g5) 14. g4 Rac8 15. h4 Qb6 16. Ne2 (16. Kb1
Rxc3 17. bxc3 e5) 16... a5 17. h5 e5 (17... a4 18. Nbd4 b4 (18... e5 19. Nf5))
18. h6 g6) 13. Kb1 b4 14. axb4 Rxb4 15. Na2 (15. Rhe1 O-O (15... Bb7) 16. Qe2
Nc5 (16... Bb7 17. Bxa6 Ra8 18. Bxb7 Qxb7) 17. Nxc5 Qxc5 18. Na2 Rb8) 15... Rb8
) (12. Kb1 b4 {The correct move forcing White's Knight is to forced to go back.
} (12... Bb7 13. Rhe1 O-O 14. a3 h6 (14... Rac8) 15. Bxh6 (15. h4 Rac8 16. g4)
15... gxh6 16. g4 Nh7 17. h4) (12... e5) 13. Ne2 (13. Nd5 exd5 14. exd5 O-O 15.
Nd4 Nc5) 13... e5 {Limiting both White's Knights.} (13... Bb7 14. Nbd4 Nc5) 14.
Ng3 g6 15. h4 (15. Rhf1 a5 {Starting our queenside play.}) 15... h5 16. f5 a5
17. fxg6 fxg6 18. Rhf1 O-O (18... a4)) (12. e5 Bb7 13. Qg3 dxe5 14. fxe5 Qxe5
15. Bf4 Qh5) 12... Bb7 (12... Qa5 13. Nd4 Qb6 14. Nb3 Qc7 15. Nd4 b4 16. Nd5
exd5 17. exd5) (12... b4 {is very scary as it allows Nd5.} 13. Nd5 exd5 14.
exd5 (14. e5)) 13. Qh3 (13. a3 Rc8 {Planning Qb6 and Rxc3 or b4.} (13... O-O
14. g4 Rac8 (14... h6 $4 15. Bxh6 (15. h4) 15... gxh6 16. h4) 15. Kb1 Qb6) 14.
g4 (14. f5 e5 {Next move can be Nb6-Nc4/a4.}) 14... Qb6 15. Ne2 (15. h4 Rxc3) (
15. Nd5 exd5 16. exd5 {White has some compensation but it is not enough as his
Knight is not on d4.} Bxd5 $2 (16... Kf8) (16... Kd8) (16... O-O $5 17. Rxe7
Bxd5 18. Bxh7+ Kxh7 19. Rxd5 Nxd5 20. Qxd5 Qg1+ 21. Kd2) 17. Rxe7+ Kf8 18. Qe2
Bxb3) 15... a5 (15... e5 16. Ng3 g6 17. Bxf6 Nxf6 18. g5 Nd7) 16. Kb1 a4 17.
Nbd4 b4 18. axb4 Qxb4) (13. Nd5 exd5 (13... Nxd5 14. exd5 Bxd5 15. Qxd5 exd5
16. Rxe7+ Kf8 17. Bf5 (17. Nd4 Rb8 18. Bf5 Rd8 19. Be6) 17... Rd8 18. Nd4 h6
19. Bg6 hxg5 20. Rxf7+ Kg8 21. Ne6) 14. exd5 Kf8) 13... b4 (13... e5 14. Kb1 b4
15. Nd5 {Opening up the lines.} Bxd5 16. exd5) (13... O-O $4 {is a huge
blunder because of e5!} 14. e5 dxe5 15. fxe5 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 (16. Bxf6 $4 Nxd3+
17. Rxd3 Bxf6) 16... Qxe5 17. Bxf6 Qf4+ 18. Kb1 g6 19. Bxe7) 14. Nb1 $2 {
after that hesitation...white has 2 very passive knights..and this is the
reason for his defeat} (14. Ne2 e5 {should be played.} (14... Nxe4 {is
impractical.} 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 16. Ned4 Nf2 (16... d5 17. f5 (17. Bxe4 dxe4 18. f5
e5 19. f6+ Nxf6 20. Nf5+ Kf8 21. Qg3 g6 22. Qg5 Ng8 23. Nd6 f6 24. Rf1 Kg7 25.
Qg4 (25. Nf5+) 25... Nh6 26. Ne8+ Raxe8 27. Rd7+)) 17. Qh4+)) (14. Nd5 {
White should play this way even if there is no compensation. As the
alternatives are too passive.} Nxd5 $6 (14... exd5 15. exd5 Kf8) 15. exd5 Bxd5
(15... Bxg5 16. fxg5 (16. dxe6 Bxf4+ 17. Kb1 Ne5) 16... Bxd5 17. g6 (17. Bg6))
16. Bxe7 Kxe7 17. Nd4 (17. f5)) 14... e5 $3 {Limiting b3-Knight and stopping
White's e5 ideas.} (14... O-O 15. e5 dxe5 16. fxe5 Nxe5 17. Rxe5 Qxe5 18. Bxf6
Bxf6 19. Qxh7#) (14... Rb8 15. Nd4 e5 16. Nf5) 15. N1d2 (15. f5 a5 16. N1d2 (
16. g4 a4 17. N3d2 a3 18. b3) 16... a4 17. Na1 b3 (17... Rc8) (17... Ba6) (
17... O-O) 18. axb3 a3) (15. fxe5 dxe5 $1 (15... Nxe5 16. Nd4)) 15... a5 16.
Kb1 (16. Nd4 {is objectively losing but this is the best move in a practical
sense. What does the computer say here? Well, the computer is switched off and
we are playing a practical game with a huge mess.} exd4 17. e5 dxe5 18. fxe5
Nxe5 19. Bb5+ Kf8 {The player who has sacrificed material for attack should
have a very safe King of his own. The problem for White is that his King is
also weak!} (19... Nc6 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21. Qh6 $4 (21. Ne4) 21... O-O-O $19) 20.
Nb3 a4 $3 {Black creates counterplay.} 21. Nxd4 b3 (21... h6 22. Bf4 Bd6 23.
Qh4 (23. Nf5 b3 24. axb3 (24. c3 bxa2 (24... a3)) 24... axb3 25. Qxb3 Ra1+ 26.
Kd2 Nf3+) 23... b3) 22. axb3 a3 23. Nf5 (23. Kb1 axb2 (23... a2+ $4 24. Ka1 $18
) 24. Nf5 Ra1+ (24... Nf3) (24... Bf3 25. gxf3 (25. Rxe5 Ra1+ (25... Qc3 26.
Ba4) 26. Kxb2 Ba3+ 27. Kxa1 Qc3+ 28. Kb1 Qb2#) 25... Ra1+ 26. Kxb2 Ba3+ 27.
Kxa1 Qc3+) (24... Qc5 $3 $19 {- 14..00 !!!}) 25. Kxb2 Nd3+ (25... Bxg2) 26.
Bxd3 (26. Rxd3 Rxe1) 26... Ba3+ 27. Kxa1 Qc3+) 23... a2 24. Kd2 Ne4+ 25. Rxe4
Bxg5+ 26. Ke2 Bxe4) 16... a4 17. Nc1 {White is worse because he has two
terrible Knights.} (17. Nd4 {was the last chance but he is too slow now.} exd4
18. e5 dxe5 19. fxe5 Nxe5 20. Bb5+ (20. Bf4 Nfd7 (20... Ra5) 21. Nc4 f6 22.
Bg6+ (22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23. Bg6+ hxg6 24. Qxh8+ Kf7 25. Qh3 Rc8 (25... d3) 26. Re2
d3 27. Rxd3 Ba6) 22... hxg6 23. Qxh8+ Kf7 24. Qh3 Qxc4) 20... Kf8 (20... Nc6
21. Bxf6 gxf6 22. Ne4 O-O (22... b3 23. Nxf6+ Kd8 (23... Kf8 24. Qh6#) 24. Bxc6
(24. Nd5 bxc2+ 25. Kxc2 Nb4+ 26. Kb1 Bxd5) 24... bxc2+ 25. Kxc2 Qxc6+ 26. Kb1
Bxf6)) 21. Qg3 (21. Bxf6 Bxf6 22. Ne4 b3 (22... Qb6 23. Bf1 b3) 23. axb3 axb3
24. Qxb3 Qa5) 21... Bd6 22. Bf4) 17... O-O 18. Ne2 (18. g4 exf4 (18... Nc5) 19.
Bxf4 Ne5 20. g5 Nfd7 21. Qg3 (21. g6 hxg6) 21... b3 (21... Rfc8) (21... Nc5)
22. axb3 axb3 23. Ncxb3 Qc6 24. Nf3 Qa4) (18. f5 Nc5 {Intending b3 with huge
attack.} 19. g4 b3 (19... Rfc8) 20. axb3 axb3) 18... Rfc8 $1 {If we can play
Rfc8 is always nice, because of Nf8/Bf8 to defend the King and create running
space for the King with Kf8-Ke8 and so on.} 19. Ng3 g6 $3 {Remember the rule:
Quite often in the Najdorf..the moves e5 and g6 fit very well together for
black!} 20. Nc4 (20. Nf5 gxf5 21. Qxf5 Kh8 (21... Ba6 22. fxe5 Bxd3 23. cxd3
Qc2+ 24. Ka1 a3 25. bxa3 Rxa3) 22. Qh3 Kg8 23. g4 a3 24. Bxf6 axb2 25. Bxe7 Qa5
) (20. f5 Nc5 (20... b3)) 20... Ba6 21. b3 axb3 22. cxb3 (22. axb3 Bxc4 23.
Bxc4 Qa5) 22... Nc5 23. Ne2 (23. Bf1 Qa7 24. Rd2 Nxb3 25. axb3 Bxc4 26. Bxc4
Qa1+ 27. Kc2 Ra2+ 28. Kd3 Qc3+ 29. Ke2 Qxd2+ 30. Kf3 Qf2#) 23... Nfxe4 24. Bxe7
Qxe7 25. Bxe4 Nxe4 26. Nb6 Qa7 27. Nxa8 (27. Nxc8 Bxc8 (27... Bd3+ 28. Qxd3
Qxa2+ 29. Kc1 Rxc8+) 28. Qf3 Qxa2+ 29. Kc1 Bf5 (29... Qa1+)) 27... Rxa8 28. a4
Bxe2 29. Rc1 Qf2 0-1

