{The straring position of this lecture arises after} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4
cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 {In this position, White's most popular
continuation is} 7. Nb3 {Usually, this move is connected with castling long
followed by a kingside attack. The most common way of attacking is f2-f3
followed by g2-g4. White, however, has different ways of handling the position.
This lecture covers all plans different that f2-f3 and g2-g4. After studying
the mateiral, you will understand that understanding and knowledge of typical
patterns is far more important than memorization of concrete lines.} ({In this
lecture, you will also learn how to fight against} 7. Nf3 {On one hand, this
move stops an early ...Be6 because of Ng5 (Black could waste a tempo with ...
h7-h6 though, and then Be6 which is also quite playable) On the other hand,
the Nf3 does not cover c5 ..so an eventual ...Nbd7-Nc5! gives Black good
counterplay. After studying the material, you will be more than confident when
facing this system.}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.Be3 & 8.h3"]
[Black "Theoretical Overview"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "46"]
[EventDate "2023.10.07"]
[SourceVersionDate "2023.10.06"]

{[%evp 0,46,32,24,43,45,82,53,48,28,44,44,44,44,44,44,44,43,23,14,0,0,0,21,32,
32,32,32,245,38,30,16,0,22,-7,-7,-7,-7,7,31,31,37,76,37,64,8,0,0,19]} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {The Najdorf.} 6. Be3 e5 {In this
lecture we will see lines without f3-g4.} 7. Nb3 Be6 {The most common move is
8...Be7 but the text move is also very good and full of traps!} 8. h3 {White
wants to play Qf3 and long castle 0-0-0. The idea is to leave his f3 square
for his queen.} (8. Nd5 {Intending Bb6 and planning to play c4.} Nbd7 {The
most accurate move with typical Najdorf play.}) 8... Nbd7 $5 {The alternatives
are also good but this move has more traps.} 9. g4 {Keep in mind 9. g4 is the
only good move for White here.} (9. f4 $6 Rc8 $1 {very strong move!} 10. f5 $2
{Normally, Black would respond with Bc4. But here the computer suggests a
better way with} Rxc3 $3 11. bxc3 Nxe4 $3 $17 {Black has a huge advantage, he
is next planning Qh4. The sample lines show it very well:} 12. Qf3 (12. fxe6 $2
Qh4+ 13. Ke2 Nxc3+ 14. Kd2 Nxd1 15. exd7+ Kxd7 16. Rxd1 Be7 17. Kc1 Rc8 $19 {
Usually, The computer likes Black in such positions if we have Queen against
some pieces.}) 12... Bd5 13. c4 Bc6 $17) (9. Bd3 {We don't need to know too
much theory for such a random move, as the typical Najdorf play continues.} Be7
10. O-O O-O 11. f4 {We now have three good options: Rc8, b5 & exf4. Concrete
play decides what is the best.} exf4 {is the best option.} 12. Bxf4 Ne5 13. Nd5
Bxd5 14. exd5 Nfd7 {Another typical idea intending Bg5 or Bf6-g6-Bg7.} 15. Qd2
Bf6) (9. Qf3 $6 {Is in fact a dubious move.} Rc8 $1 {Intending Rxc3. White
would now love to play two moves 0-0-0 and Nd5. However, he is one move slower
because of ...Rxc3} 10. Bd3 (10. O-O-O Rxc3 {This brilliant sacrifice creates
counterplay for Black on the queenside.}) 10... Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Nd5 Bxd5
13. exd5 g6 {With typical Najdorf play. White's queen on f3 is misplaced.})
9... h6 $1 {Stopping g5 to maintain the control of central square d5.} (9...
Rc8 $5 {This is also interesting and good but it is better to keep more
options for the rook.}) 10. Qd2 {Again, 10.Qd2 is the only good move. Please
learn how to treat the alternatives!} (10. Qf3 $6 {This natural-looking move
shows a lack of understanding in the Najdorf by White. Be careful because many
players will play like this.} Rc8 $1 $15 {Intending ...Rxc3!} (10... Be7 $2 {
We simply cannot play what we want. This natural move is a big mistake.} 11.
O-O-O Rc8 12. Nd5 Bxd5 13. exd5 O-O 14. Bd3 {White gets a free hand on the
Kingside.}) 11. O-O-O $2 (11. Bg2 Be7 $17 12. O-O {Now, we have two good ways:
...Nf8 and ...g5} Nf8 $3 $17 {Planning Ng6.} (12... g5 $5 $17 {Fixing the pawn
on g4 and intending h5 in the future is also good.} 13. Qd1 h5 14. f3 Nb6 $17 {
Intending ...Nc4. Our King can stay on e8 forever because White's pieces are
misplaced.}) 13. Rad1 Ng6) 11... Rxc3 12. bxc3 b5 $17 {fixing the c3 pawn.
White will face huge problems because of his weak kingside.}) (10. f4 $4 {
This move fails to pure tactics!} exf4 $3 11. Bxf4 Nh5 $3 $17 {Intending Qh4.
Black is almost winning here.} 12. Be3 (12. gxh5 Qh4+ {wins the piece back.})
12... Ng3 13. Rh2 Nxf1 14. Kxf1 h5 $17 {White's king is too weak in the middle
of the board. Black has an obvious advantage.}) (10. Qd3 {is another sideline.
We can respond with any of the standard Najdorf moves.} Rc8 (10... b5 $132) (
10... Be7 $132) 11. O-O-O b5 $132 {with typical Najdorf play.}) 10... b5 $1 {
Planning b4 and attacking on e4.} 11. O-O-O {ignoring the b4 threat.} (11. Bg2
$5 {is also possible. We can respond with Nb6 or Bc4 or Be7} Be7 $132 (11...
Nb6 $132) (11... Bc4 $5 $132)) (11. a3 $6 {passive play is generally not a
good option in the Najdorf.} Be7 12. O-O-O O-O $1 {This is a very dangerous
position for both sides as both sides have hooks. But Black has an upper hand.}
13. f4 (13. Rg1 Rc8 {Planning ...Bxb3 and Nxe4} 14. Kb1 (14. g5 {drops the
e4-pawn after the following continuation} hxg5 15. Bxg5 Bxb3 16. cxb3 Nxe4 $19)
14... Nb6 $15 {Intending Nc4} (14... Nh7 {another playable move stopping g5.})
15. g5 hxg5 16. Bxg5 Na4 $3 $17 {with good counterplay on the queenside.})
13... b4 $3 $17 {What an amazing move by the computer. We want to follow up
with a5 and open up more lines.}) 11... b4 $1 {11... Nb6 or 11... Be7 is also
possible.} (11... Nb6 {stopping Nd5.} 12. f4 Qc7 $5 {is a very intresting
novelty.}) (11... Be7 12. a3 Rc8 13. Kb1 (13. f4 $2 {drops the e4-pawn.} exf4
14. Bxf4 Bxb3 15. cxb3 Nxe4 {Please remember this trick as it happens more
than often in this line.}) 13... Nb6 $15 {with usual plans of Na4/Nc4 & d5! We
want to wait before White is half-dead on the queenside and only then castle
short. In a practical sense, it works all the time!}) 12. Nd5 a5 $5 {Not the
top computer move but also very tricky and practical. We simply want to crush
White on the queenside.} ({Another option would be:} 12... Bxd5 $5 13. exd5 a5
14. Qd3 $2 a4 15. Nd2 Be7 $15) 13. Bb5 (13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 14. Bb5+ Bd7 15. Qe2 (
15. Qd3 Be7 $36 16. Nd2 {White is planning to reroute his knight on the
d5-square.} O-O 17. Bxd7 Qxd7 18. Kb1 Qc6 {Please remember the queen is often
well placed on c6 as it controls the d5-square and helps in using the
semi-open c-file.}) 15... a4 $36 {We can next castle short and get our h8-rook
in the attack as well. Black has enough counterplay.}) 13... a4 14. Na1 (14.
Nxf6+ $2 gxf6 {very rare occurrence in the Najdorf. Apparently, the queenside
initiative speaks for itself.} 15. Na1 Qa5 16. Bc6 Rc8 17. Bd5 Bxd5 18. Qxd5
Qxd5 19. Rxd5 h5 $17 {The a1-knight is certainly not happy there. I would call
this a full piece up on the other side of the board.}) (14. Bb6 axb3 {a new
queen will appear soon. Black is clearly better.}) 14... Bxd5 $1 (14... a3 $5 {
is an interesting and complicated alternative for analysis.}) 15. exd5 Qa5 {
Heating it up. It is very hard to reach such a position OTB but it helps to
know how to play in complex situations.} 16. Bc6 (16. Qe2 Be7 17. Bc6 O-O $1
$36 {Executing our plan. White is half-dead on the queenside and we finally
castle short to get another piece in the attack; the f8-rook!}) 16... a3 $1 {
Seizing the initiative!} 17. c4 $1 {The only move to not lose immediately.} (
17. b3 Ne4 $19 {The weak dark squares and misplaced a1-knight is too much to
handle for White.}) (17. Bxa8 $4 {White simply can't take the rook as it
looses by force.} axb2+ 18. Kxb2 Qa3+ 19. Kb1 Ne4 $19 {Black will win a queen
after the unstoppable Nc3.}) 17... bxc3 18. bxc3 Rc8 19. c4 Qa6 {Planning ...
Rxc6, that Bishop is quite annoying.} 20. Qb4 Rxc6 21. dxc6 Qxc6 22. Nc2 Be7
23. Qb5 Qf3 $36 {With sufficient compensation for the exchange sacrifice.} *

