{[%evp 0,19,16,28,46,54,88,88,72,40,27,24,77,68,46,33,33,-7,3,3,3,4]} 1. e4 c5
2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f4 $1 {
Another very important line to know!} (8. g3 Nbd7 {...Ng4 should also be
considered.} 9. Bg2 Be7 {simple developlment.} 10. a4 O-O 11. O-O Nb6 {
Planning Nc4 & Rc8.}) 8... exf4 9. Bxf4 Nc6 {Now, White has two moves: Qd2, Qe2
} 10. Qe2 $1 {White will next plan h3-g4 and long castling.} (10. Qd2 {You
need to know a little bit of theory against this variation.} d5 $1 {important
break to memorize} 11. O-O-O (11. exd5 {forces an equal endgame.} Nxd5 12. Nxd5
Qxd5 13. Qxd5 Bxd5 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. g3 $5 {Intending Bh3.} Bd6 $3 {
Important intermezzo to create space for our king.} 16. Bh3+ Kc7 $132) 11...
Bb4 $36 {important move with counterplay.} 12. Qd3 (12. Qe3 $2 d4 $3 $17 13.
Nxd4 Bc5 14. Nxe6 Bxe3+ 15. Bxe3 fxe6 16. Rxd8+ Rxd8 $17) 12... Bxc3 13. Qxc3
O-O $1 {Black is slightly better in these complications.} 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Qg3
Rc8 16. Bd6 Re8 $36) (10. h3 $2 {stopping Bg4 threats, but this is too slow.}
d5 $36 (10... Rc8 $3 {is also possible.} 11. Qe2 g6 $3 {Planning Bg7 and
controlling the f5-square.})) (10. Bd3 {planning short castle. The following
line is very instructive and shows the major plans in this line.} Be7 11. O-O
O-O 12. Kh1 Rc8 {In such positions, we always prefer to keep our Knight on c6
to stop Nd4 and Nf5 plans.} 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. exd5 Ne5 15. c3 Nfd7 {Planning
Bf6.} 16. Nd4 g6 17. Qd2 Bf6 18. Nf3 Nxf3 19. Rxf3 Ne5 {with equality.}) 10...
Rc8 $3 {This move without Be7, In fact, appears to be even better than in the
Be6-Be7 variation! We are on concrete grounds.} (10... Be7 {is the main move
but not my recommendation.} 11. O-O-O (11. h3 {planning 0-0-0} Nd7 {common
manuever to prepare Ne5} 12. O-O-O Nce5 13. Kb1 Rc8 14. Nd5 (14. Qe3 O-O 15.
Nd4 (15. g4 h5 16. gxh5 (16. g5 g6)) 15... Re8 16. g4 Qa5 17. a3 Bf8 18. g5)
14... Bxd5 15. exd5 O-O 16. g4 Re8 17. Qg2 {White is next planning g5 to stop
Bf6 plans.} Bg5 {Trading the dark-squared Bishops is always beneficial for us.}
18. Bg3 Bf6) 11... Bg4) 11. h3 {stopping Bg4.} g6 $3 {Amazing move! This is a
combination of tactics and strategy. We are intending Nh5.} 12. O-O-O $2 {
is in fact very bad for White. But most players will play it!} (12. Qd2 $1 {
It's amazing...but this is probably the only good move here!!! together with
12.qe3 ....practically that's impossible to find for white!} d5 13. e5 Nh5 $19
14. Bg5 Be7 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. O-O-O Ng3) (12. g4 $2 {White thinks that he will
play h4-h5 exploiting g7-g6. But we have a deep idea prepared.} h5 $3 $15 {
SOS! This is very strong for black because it forces white to close the
kingside and then we castle short. Of course, it only happens if white plays
g4 prematurely!} 13. g5 Nd7 14. O-O-O Nce5 {Our King will be super safe on the
computer.} 15. Qe3 Qc7 $3 16. Kb1 (16. Be2 Nb6 (16... Bg7) 17. Nd4 Bg7 $17)
16... Nb6 $15 {Black has a big advantage.}) 12... Nh5 13. Bh2 (13. g3 {simply
looses a plan to:} Nxg3 14. Bxg3 Qg5+ 15. Kb1 Qxg3) 13... Ng3 $1 14. Bxg3 Qg5+
15. Kb1 Qxg3 16. Qd3 Qe5 {This position is really good for Black with good
attacking prospects.} *

