{[%evp 0,20,41,14,43,43,80,42,61,30,34,30,74,41,37,47,80,49,56,13,37,23,15]} 1.
e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 {White
retreated his knight to f3 instead of b3. On one hand, this stops an early Be6
move because of Ng5 (I could waste a move with h6 though, and then Be6 is also
quite playable) On the other hand, the Nf3 does not cover c5 ..so an eventual
Nbd7-Nc5! gives black good counterplay...when we go Nc5, if he retreats with
Nf3-d2 then we play Be6 and Ned7-Rac8 etc. (Reaching positions from the 6.
Be2-e5 7.Nb3 variation.)} Qc7 $5 {an interesting line. Our main aim is to
prevent Bc4. The main line is 7...Be7!?} (7... h6 {is the simple move for the
lazy player. We are stopping Ng5 ideas and want to continue with Be6, Be7,
Nbd7, etc.}) 8. a4 Be7 $1 {In this variation Black's plan usually includes:
Qc7-Be7-0-0 Nbd7-Nc5!} (8... h6 $5 {also simple and good! The downside of this
move is when we finally go Nbd7-Nc5 he may play 1.Nd5 Nxd5 2.exd5 and in this
structure, h6 looks like a small waste of time. Sill that position is 100
percent playable!} 9. Be2 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. a5 Be6 {As we have stopped Ng5
it makes sense to place our Bishop on e6.} 12. Nd2 (12. Nd5 $5 Nxd5 13. exd5
Bg4 $1 {This position is also playable although ...h6 looks like a waste of
time.}) 12... Nbd7 {is taking us once again in the 6.Be2-e5 7.Nb3 variation})
9. a5 (9. Qe2 $6 {Planning Qc4 but this plan is too slow.} Nc6 $1 {We want to
place our knight on b4 to enhance our control of d5-square.} 10. Qc4 $2 (10. g3
Nb4 11. Bg2 Nxe4 $17 {The tactics seem to favor Black.}) 10... Be6 11. Nd5 Nxd5
12. exd5 Qa5+ $17 {winning the d5-pawn.}) (9. Bg5 {planning Bxf6 to gain
control of the d5-square.} Nbd7 {Intending to recapture on f6 with the knight
to keep the control of d5-square. The central square d5 matters a lot in these
positions.} 10. Be2 h6 $1 (10... b6 $2 {this is the typical mistake that even
very strong grandmasters have made! This type of position..which can occur by
various move orders, is actually very bad for black, as he lacks plans.} 11.
Nd2 $1 Bb7 12. O-O O-O 13. Bc4 $1 {White is simply better. He will one day
maneuver his knight on d5.}) 11. Bh4 (11. Be3 Nc5 12. Bxc5 Qxc5 {We always
recapture with the Queen!} (12... dxc5 $2 13. Bc4)) 11... g5 $1 {Executing our
plan.} 12. Bg3 Nc5 {with very strong play for Black.}) (9. Nd2 {Hoping for
Nc4-Ne3-Nd5, but that is too optimistic.} Be6 $1 $132 {simply stopping Nc4.}) (
9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Nbd7 {Planning Nc5 as White's knight is not on b3.} 11. a5
Nc5 $132) 9... O-O $1 10. Be2 (10. Bb6 $6 {This line is better for Black
because of concrete reasons.} Qc6 11. Nd5 (11. Ra4 $6 {Planning Rc4.} Be6 {
stopping Rc4} 12. Ng5 Nbd7 13. Nxe6 Nxb6 $1 {Important intermezzo to secure
space for our queen.} 14. axb6 fxe6 15. Bc4 d5 $3 {With a good position.})
11... Nxd5 12. exd5 Qe8 {Planning f5 and Qg6 next.}) 10... Nbd7 (10... Qc6 $5 {
The queen is often well placed on c6 in such situations. As it controls the d5
square & creates counterplay on the c-file.} 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Qe8 {
That's a funny manuever. We are planning f5 & Qg6.}) (10... Bd8 $1 {This
amazing move also appears to be very good. We simply want to improve our
bishop.} 11. Bb6 Qe7 12. Bxd8 Rxd8 13. O-O Be6 $132 {If our bad bishop is
exchanged, we have no major problems.}) 11. O-O (11. Bg5 h6 12. Bh4 g5 $1 {
When the Knight is on f3, h6-g5 makes complete sense! Even with our King on g8.
} 13. Bg3 Nc5 14. Nd2 Be6 15. O-O Rfd8 $132) 11... Nc5 12. Nd5 (12. Bxc5 $6
Qxc5 $1 $15 {Please remember we always recapture with the queen after Bxc5.} (
12... dxc5 $2 13. Bc4 $1 $14 {followed by Nd5. White is better.})) 12... Nxd5
13. exd5 {Intending to push c4 and b4.} Bf5 $1 (13... f5 $5 14. Nd2 Nd7 {
Threatning f4 and planning Nf6,b6.}) 14. c4 (14. b4 $2 {is weakning too much!}
Ne4 $36) 14... e4 $1 {Hoping for Nd3.} 15. Nd4 Bg6 16. b4 Nd3 17. Bxd3 exd3 18.
Rc1 Rac8 19. Qd2 Bf6 $15 {Our Bishops & the d3-pawn are really gems for us.} *

