32,16,16,16,-15,-3,-11,-14,-13,13,-25,21,-59,19,-8,53,23,107,33,104,104,208,
167,160,174,163,136,162,167,167,152,171,172,183,183,193,193,175,186,186,190]} 
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. h3
Nbd7 9. g4 {White can also change tracks with a4 planning Be2-0-0} h6 10. Qd2
b5 {I prefer this move over ...Rc8 to be more flexible.} 11. O-O-O b4 12. Nd5
Bxd5 {12... a5 is my recommendation.} 13. exd5 a5 14. Qd3 a4 15. Nd2 Be7 16.
Kb1 O-O 17. Rg1 Ra5 {Basic idea in this line.} (17... a3 {In the past, Engines
would always say this is a good move in such positions. However, after b3 if
nothing happens we may simply loose flexibility. As a human, it is important
to keep this flexiblity as long as possible.} 18. b3 Nb6 $17) 18. g5 {White
won the game in the end but the opening played no big role in it. And Black
had a good game.} hxg5 19. Bxg5 e4 20. Qg3 Rxd5 21. Bh6 Nh5 22. Qg2 Nb6 23. Be2
g6 24. Bxf8 Bxf8 25. Nxe4 Nf4 26. Qf3 Nxe2 27. Nf6+ Kg7 28. Nxd5 Nxg1 29. Rxg1
Nxd5 30. Qxd5 Qf6 31. Rg4 Qxf2 32. Qd4+ 1-0

