{This lecture deals with the most important system of the entire 6.Be3
variation arising after} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6.
Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. f3 {White is planning to proceed with Qd2 followed by ...
0-0-0 and g2-g4. Having withstood the test of the time, this attacking setups
is considered very challenging. Black's most practical solution against this
line is} h5 $1 {For many years now, this move is considered to be the best! We
are stopping g2-g4 for many moves. However, the downside is that the h5-pawn
can also be a hook after Black castles short. Now, White has two main ideas:
castling short or caslting long. These ideas can be combined with Nd5 or not.
In this lecture, you will learn all the important nuances related to these
plans. As usual, understanding is far more important than knowledge of
concrete theory.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.Be3 e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.f3 h5"]
[Black "Theoretical Review"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "36"]
[EventDate "2023.10.07"]
[SourceTitle "CBM 089 Extra"]
[Source "ChessBase"]
[SourceDate "2002.09.10"]
[SourceVersion "2"]
[SourceVersionDate "2002.09.10"]
[SourceQuality "1"]

{[%evp 0,13,28,10,55,47,73,46,46,18,33,17,49,37,36,39]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3.
d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 (6. f3 {is also a possible moveorder.} e5
7. Nb3 Be6 {Transposes into the mainline.}) 6... e5 7. Nb3 Be6 {One of the
absolute main lines and the most important position in this line.} 8. f3 (8.
Qd2 $1 {The immediate Qd2 is another very important line that you should know
well. White omits f3 and plans 0-0-0 followed by f2-f4. The drawback is that
the e4 pawn will be weak.} Nbd7 9. O-O-O (9. f4 {Against the immediate f4, We
can respond with b5 or Rc8.} b5 $1 {is the simpler solution.} (9... Rc8 $1 {
Objectively the best move.} 10. f5 Bxb3 11. axb3 d5 $36 {Important break
activating our f8-Bishop.} 12. exd5 Bb4 $17) 10. f5 Bc4 $132 {with typical
Najdorf play.}) 9... Be7 10. f3 h5 {stopping g4 ideas is important.} 11. Kb1 b5
$132 {We have transposed into the mainline.}) 8... h5 $1 {For many years now,
this move is considered to be the best! We are stopping g4 for many moves.
However, the downside is that this can also be a hook after Black castle's
short. Now, White has two main ideas: casting short or caslting long. These
ideas can be combined with Nd5 or not.} 9. Nd5 $1 {Forcing us to capture on d5.
} (9. Qd2 $1 {This is the other mainline where white wants to castle long and
postpones Nd5.} Nbd7 {Playing the obvious moves first!} (9... Be7 {Please
remmember this is the wrong moveorder!} 10. Nd5 Bxd5 11. exd5 {We want our
Bishop on g7 and not e7!}) 10. O-O-O $5 {Now Black has several good moves here
with typical Najdorf play. Please remember you don't need to memorize these
lines here. Just knowing the typical plans is enough! Our plans include moves
like Be7-Qc7 or Rc8 first... b5-Nb6-Nc4, or b5-b4, etc etc...and at a good
moment we may castle! Also, against 1.h3 we always respond with ...h4!} (10.
Nd5 Bxd5 11. exd5 g6 {transposes.}) 10... Be7 $1 {Staying flexible with our
choice of Rc8 or Rb8.} 11. Kb1 (11. Nd5 Nxd5 $1 {We don't have to give up our
Bishop if we are not forced to.} 12. exd5 Bf5 $132 {with pressure on the
c-file. If allowed we would love to trade the dark-squared bishops with Bg5.})
11... Qc7 12. Bd3 b5 13. a3 (13. Bg5 {The g5-square is weak but it doesn't
matter so much in such positions.} O-O 14. f4 Rfc8 $15 {with huge attacking
chances.}) 13... Nb6 $36 {Planning Nc4/Na4 - Rc8. Black's play flows itself.})
9... Bxd5 (9... Nbd7 $2 {Please remember this typical mistake. If the e4-pawn
is supported 1.c4 is a huge positional threat after Nd5. We should never ever
allow a maroczy bind and capture on d5-immediately!} 10. c4 $16 Bxd5 {We can
still capture on d5 but that means we also lack a lot more space.} 11. cxd5 {
Keeping a Bishop pair and space advantage.}) (9... Nxd5 $5 {is the best choice.
} 10. exd5 Bf5) 10. exd5 Nbd7 {Playing the most obvious or certain moves
first! Think about it, The knight was supposed to go on d7 and there was no
other square available. So, it can't be a wrong placement. However, if you
played something like Be7 or Rc8 it means plans like g6-Bh6 and Rb8-b5-b4 are
never possible.} 11. Qd2 (11. Be2 g6 12. O-O $2 {This is a common mistake and
Black is immediately better after 12...Bh6!} (12. Qd2 {should be played to
stop Bh6.} Bg7 13. O-O b6 {important move to stop Na5 ideas!}) 12... Bh6 $17 {
Forcing the trade of bishops. Black is better.}) 11... g6 {Our Bishop belongs
on g7 and not on e7.} 12. Be2 $5 {A very useful move, White doesn't declare
his plans yet. will he castle long or short?} (12. O-O-O $1 Bg7 13. Kb1 $1 {
This is the most logical try; a very useful move in any case. Getting ready to
play c2-c4 in case black tries 13...Nb6?} (13. Qb4 {not a big deal at all! ...
white just gets a worse version of the main line... with the queen misplaced
on b4} Qc7 14. Na5 b5 15. Nc6 O-O $132 {The c6-Knight doesn't matter a lot. We
always have tricks to capture on d5 and e4.}) (13. h3 b5 $1 {It is important
to first play ...b5 before Nb6-Nc4 ideas.} 14. Na5 Nb6 15. Nc6 Qc7 16. Bxb6 {
White is forced to give up his Bishop pair. Usually in such positions, Black
is always better.} Qxb6 $15) (13. c4 $6 a5 $1 $15 {Now that White can't
control the b5-square, It makes sense to push a5 planning a4-a3.}) 13... Qc7 $1
{stopping c2-c4.} 14. h3 (14. h4 $6 {is too slow.} e4 $132 {Black will have
huge attacking chances just like in the dragon.}) 14... h4 $5 15. Bg5 Nb6 $132
{White is forced to give up his Bishop pair which means we are better.}) (12.
Na5 {With Na5, White plans b4-c4 and crushes us on the queenside. However,
this also abounds center and we will respond with qc7 and a quick e4 advance!}
Qc7 13. Be2 Bg7 14. O-O e4 $1 $132 {is the correct move!} 15. f4 (15. c4 {
is also possible. But we always have enough counterplay on the e-file because
of the weak squares e4,e3,e2.} exf3 16. Bxf3 O-O $132) 15... Ng4 $1 {Black is
better and we are in concrete grounds.} 16. Bxg4 hxg4) 12... Bg7 (12... b6 $2 {
stopping Na5 and anticipating short castling. But White can trick us with
castling long and no doubt ...b6 would be a waste of time there.} 13. O-O-O $1
{Unfortunately the plan with b6 works only after White plays 0-0. If we play
b6 too early he can castle long and we are too slow with our attack!}) 13. O-O
$5 (13. O-O-O $5 b5 $1 {Now, we can see the advantage of not committing with ..
.b6 too early.} 14. Na5 Nb6 15. Nc6 Qc7 $36 {the knight on c6 is hitting
nowhere! Usually, it is well placed on c6 if it can target the e7-Bishop.}) (
13. Na5 $5 Qc7 14. c4 e4 $1 $132 {Following our typical plan! Please remmember
to play ...e4 If white goes away from the center too soon.}) (13. a4 b6 {
with typical plans.}) 13... b6 $1 {the best move; stopping Na5! Again we do
not need to memorize anything. Just know the typical plans & ideas.} 14. c4 (
14. a4 O-O 15. a5 $6 (15. c4 $2 a5 $15 {Typical response as the b5-square is
not controlled by White.} 16. Rac1 Nc5 17. Nxc5 bxc5 {Black is better.}) 15...
b5 16. c4 bxc4 17. Bxc4 Qc7 {planning Qb7 to target the d5-pawn.} 18. Rac1 (18.
Ra4 Rab8 $1 19. Rc1 (19. Bxa6 Rxb3) 19... Qb7 $17) 18... Qb7 $15 {We can
continue to fight for the initiative}) 14... h4 $1 {The Dzwikowski line! ( new
in chess yearbook 138) Black intends to continue with Nf6-h5 and f7-f5
starting a kingside initiative (New in chess.) Of course, we can castle as
well.} (14... O-O {Our plan can be Nh7-f5-Bf6-Bg5 or Re8 or a5! as the
b5-square is not controlled by the Bishop. The position will be calm.}) 15. Bg5
{stopping Nh5.} Qc7 $1 {Planning Nh5.} 16. Rae1 (16. Bd3 $6 {Is also possible
hoping to open up the center quickly. However, we are too close to castling.}
h3 17. g3 O-O $17 {Dunop-Bellman ICCF 2019 turned out to be disastrous for
white !} 18. Rac1 Rfe8 19. Qf2 a5 20. a4 e4 $3 {The tactics favour Black.})
16... Kf8 $1 {Artifical castling, yah!} 17. Kh1 (17. f4 {is very complicated.
Again, please don't memorize these lines.} Ne4 $36 18. Qc2 f5 {The g5-Bishop
is stuck and surprisingly White can't open up the center.}) (17. Bd3 {planning
f4} Re8 $132 {planning to meet f4 with e4!} 18. f4 $2 e4 $15 {If we can open
up the h8-a1 diagonal without much trouble it usually means something horrible
happened for White.}) 17... Kg8 $5 18. Bd3 Nh5 $3 {Just following our typical
plans. We have Ng3 ideas in the air.} *

