{[%evp 0,57,19,24,37,37,70,51,51,24,37,30,60,29,29,29,29,29,55,52,59,27,37,37,
37,3,0,-8,-11,3,-12,2,-5,-55,-37,-54,-74,-70,-49,-46,6,-20,51,19,-7,-5,-15,-15,
-696,-29987,-29988,-29989,-29990,-29991,-29992,-29995,-29996,-29997,-29998,
-29999] An amazing game by the young expert! First White commits the big
positional mistake of allowing Bh6! Next, he plays another very bad move 14.
Kh1 into the line fo fire ! You can enjoy the rest of the game by yourself!!} 
1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. f3 e5 7. Nb3 Be6 8. Be3
h5 (8... Be7 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O a5 11. a4 Nc6 12. g4 Nb4) 9. Be2 Nbd7 10. Nd5
Bxd5 (10... Nxd5 11. exd5 Bf5 12. O-O Be7 13. f4 (13. Bd3 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 O-O 15.
f4)) 11. exd5 g6 12. O-O $2 {Remember this rule : in positions where white has
played the move ed5, black wants to exhange the dark square bishop...and white
does not!!} (12. Qd2 Ng8 (12... Bg7 13. O-O b6 14. a4 O-O 15. a5 b5 16. c4 bxc4
17. Bxc4 Qc7 18. Rfc1 Qb7)) 12... Bh6 $1 $17 {It is no surprise, Black is
already better.} 13. Bxh6 (13. Bf2 Kf8 $1 $17 (13... O-O $17)) 13... Rxh6 14.
Qd2 Rh8 15. Kh1 $2 {This is a very bad move, It appears that White is moving
his King to safety but in fact he is not!} h4 $1 16. Rfd1 Nh5 17. Qe3 Nf4 18.
Bf1 Nf6 $3 19. c4 N6h5 20. Rd2 Qg5 21. Re1 (21. Kg1 Nh3+) 21... Ng3+ 22. Kg1
Nf5 23. Qc3 Nh3+ 24. Kh1 Ng3+ 25. hxg3 Nf2+ 26. Kg1 hxg3 27. Rxf2 Rh1+ 28. Kxh1
Qh4+ 29. Kg1 {This was one of the best combinations, I have ever seen.} 0-1

