{The subject of this lecture is the position arising after} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 {This is a very interesting and
complicated system. White is ready to meet 6...e6 with 7.g4, thus getting a
Keres Attack type of position. As always, we will stick to the genuine Najdorf
positions by playing} e5 {In this position, White's most common move is 7.Nde2,
but in my opinion, 7.Nb3 is even better. The arising positions are
strategically very complex. Every little positional nuance can dramatically
change the evaluation of the position. Besides providing you with a reliable
repertoire against 6.h3, this lecture will improve your general chess
understanding.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.h3 e5"]
[Black "Theoretical Review"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "150"]
[EventDate "2023.10.07"]
