[SourceQuality "1"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 {A very interesting
and complicated system for White!} e5 {Black has other alternatives, like 6...
e6, which is very interesting and complicated... but once again I'd rather
stick to the traditional Najdorf approach!} (6... e6) (6... Nc6 $5) 7. Nde2 $5
{This is the most common move, but in my view 7.Nb3 is better!} (7. Nf3 {
And here we will follow the typical Nf3 strategies.} Qc7 8. Bg5 (8. g4 {
This is an interesting move... and a new trend.} h6 $1 {We need to prserve the
knight on f6, therefore we prepare to recapture on g5 instead of retreating
with the knight.} 9. g5 (9. Be3 b5 $5 10. g5 hxg5 11. Nxg5 Bb7 $132 {The
position is highly double-edged, but Black is ready to establish the typical
Najdorf set-up and should be comfortable.}) 9... hxg5 10. Nxg5 Be6 {We don't
fear White trading on e6 as we increase control over the d5-square in this
scenario.} 11. Be3 Nc6 $1 $132 12. Qd2 O-O-O $5 {with the idea of 13.0-0-0 d5
and} (12... Qa5 $5) 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. exd5 Nd4 15. Bxd4 exd4 16. O-O-O Rh4 $1
$11 {with an equal opposite-coloured bishops game.}) 8... Nbd7 9. a4 Be7 10.
Be2 h6 11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 Nc5 13. Nd2 Be6) (7. Nb3 h6 $5 {By choosing this
rare move order instead 7...Be7, we rule out the 8.g4?! continuation because
of the fast ...Be6!-d5 line!} (7... Be6 $6 8. f4 exf4 9. Bxf4 Nc6 10. Qe2 $16 {
WHITE IS AN IMPORTANT TEMPO UP IN THE 6.Be3 e5 7.Nb3 Be6 8.f4 exf4 9.Bxf4 Nc6
10.Qe2 line ..because he played Bc1xf4 in one move and he has the extra very
useful h3 move!}) 8. Be3 (8. g4 $6 Be6 $1 9. Be3 (9. Bg2 $6 Nbd7 10. a4 Be7 {
White is overextended and castling to neither side is particularly attractive
for him.} 11. Be3 (11. O-O Rc8 $15 12. a5 g5 $3 $15 {Preparing to entrench a
knight on f4! Black is doing great, e.g.} 13. Nd5 Nf8 14. Be3 Ng6 $17 15. Qd2
Nf4) 11... Nf8 $3 $15 {Remember this maneuver in this structure. The knight on
g6, ready to spring to f4 or h4 will be a big nuisance for White.}) {There
will be a tempo against the rook on h1.} 9... d5 $1 (9... Nbd7 $5 10. Qd2) 10.
exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. Rg1 Nc6 13. Qd2 Rc8 {White can't really castle
long now because of ...Nb4 ideas.} 14. c3 (14. O-O-O $4 Nb4 $19) 14... Be7 15.
Rd1 (15. O-O-O $4 Nb4 $17) (15. Bg2 $6 Bxg2 16. Qxd8+ (16. Rxg2 $6 Qc7 $1 17.
O-O-O b5 $15 {Black is more active and some of White's pieces are a bit awkward
here.}) 16... Nxd8 $1 17. Rxg2 Ne6 $15 {We have a slightly better endgame for
Black thanks to the superbly placed knight, the awkward rook on g2, and some
weak squares in White's camp.} 18. Ke2 (18. O-O-O b5 $15) 18... Bg5 $15) 15...
Be6 16. Nc5 {White sacrifices a pawn for the bishop pair. Other lines are not
very threatening.} Qxd2+ 17. Rxd2 Bxc5 18. Bxc5 Bxa2 19. Rg3 Be6 $11 {White
holds no more than sufficient compensation.}) 8... Be7 9. g4 Nbd7 $1 {A very
original and good plan... which works only in this line!} (9... b5 $5 {is
another good way to play!} 10. Nd5 Bb7 $1 (10... Nbd7) 11. Bb6 Qc8 12. Nc7+ Kf8
13. Nxa8 Bxa8 $132 {The compensation for the exchange looks very appealing.
The game becomes highly unbalanced, of course.}) 10. a4 $1 {ONCE AGAIN THE
ONLY GOOD MOVE FOR WHITE... AND WHEN YOU SEE SUCH A NOTE PAY A LOT OF
ATTENTION. .. BECAUSE WHITE WILL NOT FIND THE BEST MOVE!} (10. Bg2 $6 b5 $1 $15
{Black has achieved the desired set-up without disruption.} 11. O-O O-O $15 12.
a4 b4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Rb8 $15 {Remember that in these positions the ...
h5 move can become a big problem for White!}) (10. Qd2 $2 {There's no time for
the long castle set-up.} b5 11. a3 (11. a4 Bb7 $132) (11. f3 $2 Bb7 12. O-O-O
b4 $17 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. exd5 a5) (11. O-O-O Bb7 $17 {White has problems
holding everything together.}) 11... Bb7 12. f3 d5 $1 $17 {Black breaks open
the centre before White consolidates his position.}) (10. f3 $6 b5 11. a4 bxa4
$5 (11... b4 $5 12. Nd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Rb8 14. O-O-O Nb6 15. Qa5 Bd7 16. Bxa6
Nxa4 {1/2-1/2 McDermott, F-Fluit,J/ICCF 2020/Nikos Updates}) 12. Rxa4 O-O $132)
10... Nf8 $1 (10... Qc7 $5) 11. Qd2 $1 (11. Bc4 $1 {Possibly the best!} Ng6 $5
(11... Be6 $5 12. Bxe6 fxe6 13. Qd3 Rc8 14. O-O-O Ng6 $132) 12. Qe2 (12. a5 Be6
$36) {USUALLY WE WILL PLAY ...Ng6 AND ...Be6 BUT IN THIS PARTICULAR POSITION ..
.Bd7 APPEARS TO BE THE BEST!} 12... Bd7 $1 13. f3 (13. O-O-O b5 14. axb5 axb5
15. Bxb5 O-O 16. Kb1 Qc7 $36 (16... Be6 $36)) 13... Rc8 14. h4 d5 $3 $15 {
,S-Bernal Varela,N/FICGS email 2010/Corr/[ 0-1 NEW}) (11. a5 $6 {White
overextends here. Black will get the better prospects:} Be6 12. Nd5 Rc8 $1 $15
13. Qd3 Ng6 14. O-O-O O-O $15 (14... Nxd5 15. exd5 Bd7 16. Kb1 Bg5 $132)) 11...
Be6 (11... Ng6 {is the same}) 12. O-O-O (12. f4 $2 exf4 13. Bxf4 Ng6 $17 {
Black is going to castle short and then the ...b5 gambit will come out strong.}
14. Be3 O-O 15. O-O-O b5 $17) 12... Ng6 13. Nd5 $1 (13. Kb1 O-O 14. f3 b5 $36 {
Typically, this gambit leaves White with serious practical problems.}) (13. f3
Nd7 $1 {White may later pay for this a4-0-0-0 combination with a well-timed...
b7-b5 gambit!} 14. Nd5 (14. Kb1 O-O 15. a5 b5 $1 $15 {Black achieves an
initiative with energetic play, e.g.} (15... b6 $5) 16. axb6 Nxb6 $17 17. h4
Qc7 ({Not} 17... Bxh4 $4 18. Qxd6 $18) 18. h5 Nf4 19. Bxf4 exf4 20. Qxf4 Rfc8
$17 {White's pawn advantage is not very relevant considering Black's coming
queenside onslaught.}) 14... Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Qc7 16. Qc4 $5 Qb8 17. Rd3 {This is
the engine's suggested method of playing, not so easy to come up with over the
board. White starts playing along the c-file.} (17. a5 O-O 18. Kb1 Rc8 19. Qd5
Qc7 20. Rh2 b5 $1 $15 {In a typical manner, ...b5 comes, causing White some
discomfort.}) (17. Kb1 O-O 18. Rd3 $4 {Now the 17.Rd3 idea is not possible:}
Rc8 19. Qb4 d5 20. Qe1 d4 $19) 17... O-O 18. Rc3 Nc5 $1 {Black has to prevent
the idea of Qc7, as he doesn't want to trade the queens.} 19. a5 (19. Nxc5 dxc5
20. a5 Qc7 21. Qa4 (21. Bxc5 $2 Qxa5 22. Bxe7 Qa1+ 23. Kd2 Nxe7 $19) 21... Bg5
22. Bxg5 hxg5 23. Bc4 Rfd8 $132 {White has a nice bishop, but Black is strong
on the dark squares.}) 19... Ne6 $132 {...Bg5 with dark-squared play on the
kingside is the main plan. The position remains double-edged.}) 13... Rc8 $1 {
A universally good reaction to Nd5 in these lines.} 14. Qb4 (14. Nxf6+ $2 {
It is very lame to dispose of the central knight in this way.} Bxf6 15. Kb1 Qd7
$3 $17 {Black targets the a4-pawn and achieves a big advantage.} 16. Qxd6 Qxa4)
(14. f3 $2 {Again, a lame move.} Nxd5 15. exd5 Bd7 16. a5 Bg5 $17 (16... Ba4
$17)) (14. Nxe7 $4 Qxe7 $19 {White just loses material.} 15. Kb1 Nxe4 16. Qd3
d5 $19) (14. Bb6 $2 Qd7 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 $17 {Too many links in White's camp
have become targets.}) 14... Bxd5 15. exd5 Qc7 16. c3 Nd7 $132 {The idea on
the agenda is ...Bg5.}) 7... h5 {We stop g2-g4 and suppress the e2-knight.} (
7... Be6 $6 {is an example of White's idea working without hindrance:} 8. g4 h6
9. Bg2 Nbd7 10. O-O Be7 11. Ng3 $36) 8. Bg5 $5 (8. g3 $5 {This is the other
main move of the system.} Be7 9. Bg2 (9. a4 $6 {This is premature and it
allows the typical ...Nc6-Nb4! idea!} Nc6 10. Bg2 Nb4 11. O-O Be6 $132 12. f4
$2 {This advance only worsens White's situation.} (12. Bg5 Qd7 13. h4 Rc8 $132
{This pin of the c3-knight will be typically very annoying for White.} (13...
Ng4 $132)) (12. b3 O-O 13. Ba3 a5 $132 {...d5 is still possible at some point.
...Rc8 can pin the knight.}) 12... Rc8 13. Be3 Qd7 14. Kh2 h4 15. f5 Bc4 16. g4
d5 17. exd5 Nbxd5 18. Bf2 Nxc3 19. Nxc3 Bxf1 20. Qxf1 Qc7 21. Kh1 Bc5 22. g5
Nh5 23. Nd5 Qd8 24. Bxh4 Nf4 25. Nxf4 Rxh4 26. Re1 Kf8 27. Rxe5 Rxf4 28. Qxf4
Bd6 29. f6 gxf6 30. gxf6 Bxe5 31. Qxe5 Rxc2 32. Qg5 Qd1+ 33. Kh2 Qd6+ 34. Kh1
Rxb2 35. Qg7+ Ke8 36. Qg8+ Qf8 37. Qh7 Rb6 38. Bxb7 Rxf6 39. Qd3 Qe7 40. Bg2
Qe1+ 41. Kh2 Qe5+ 42. Kh1 Qa1+ 43. Kh2 Qxa4 44. Qd5 Qf4+ 45. Kh1 Re6 {0-1
Beukema,S-Ter Sahakyan,S/Terme Catez SLO 2021}) 9... b5 10. Nd5 $1 {Pretty
much THE ONLY GOOD MOVE FOR WHITE!. .. because we are threatening the .. .
b5-Nbd7 combination against a Bg2 set-up, which is always favourable for
Black! Remember this important Najdorf rule! I show a lot of sample lines
after other moves, but we don't need to know concrete theory there, only plans
and ideas.} (10. Bg5 $6 {It is enough to present a few games where White gets
outplayed after choosing this flawed method of play:} Nbd7 11. h4 (11. Bxf6 $2
Nxf6 12. a4 b4 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Be6 15. Qd2 a5 $17 (15... h4 16. g4 Bg5
17. Qxb4 Rb8 18. Qa3 Qa5+ 19. c3 Rb3 20. Qxd6 Rxb2 21. O-O Rb6 22. Qd3 O-O 23.
f4 Qc5+ 24. Kh1 Bc4 25. Qf3 Bxf4 26. Nxf4 Bxf1 27. Nd5 Bxg2+ 28. Qxg2 Rb7 29.
Rf1 Rfb8 30. Qf3 Qd6 31. g5 Qe6 32. Qd3 a5 33. Rg1 Rb2 34. Rg4 Rf2 35. Kg1 Ra2
36. Rxh4 Qd6 37. Kh1 Rbb2 38. Rg4 Ra1+ 39. Rg1 Rxg1+ 40. Kxg1 Qa3 41. Ne3 Qa1+
42. Nf1 Qc1 43. h4 Qf4 44. Qh3 Qf2+ 45. Kh1 Rb1 {0-1 Biastoch,B-Paehtz,T/
Magdeburg GER 2021})) 11... Bb7 $15 (11... Nb6) 12. a3 Rc8 13. O-O O-O 14. Qd2
Qb6 15. Be3 Qc7 16. Rac1 Nb6 17. b3 Rfd8 18. Nd5 Nbxd5 19. exd5 Qd7 20. c4 Re8
21. f3 bxc4 22. bxc4 a5 23. Kh2 Qa4 24. Nc3 Qxc4 25. Bh3 Rb8 26. Rfd1 Qa6 27.
a4 Qa8 28. g4 hxg4 29. fxg4 Bc8 30. Nb5 Bxg4 31. Nc7 Qb7 32. Rg1 Bxh3 33. Nxe8
Rxe8 34. Kxh3 Qd7+ 35. Kh2 Ng4+ 36. Kh1 Bxh4 37. Rg2 Qf5 38. Qe2 Nxe3 39. Qxe3
g6 40. Kg1 Rb8 41. Kh2 Kg7 42. Rc7 Rb4 43. Rc6 Re4 44. Qd2 Rf4 45. Rxd6 Bf2 {
0-1 Abdumalik,Z-Nihal,S/chess24.com INT 2021}) (10. a4 $6 b4 11. Nd5 a5 $3 {
and this is the amazing move... restricting the Ne2!} 12. c3 ({An internet
blitz. White won, but had big issues, including being lost, along the way:} 12.
Nxe7 Qxe7 13. Bg5 Be6 14. O-O Qc7 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. c3 Na6 17. f4 Qb6+ 18. Kh2
Nc5 19. Ng1 Rd8 20. Qe2 Bb3 21. Nf3 Bxa4 22. Nh4 Bb5 23. c4 Bd7 24. fxe5 dxe5
25. Rad1 Bc8 26. Rd5 a4 27. Qf2 Rxd5 28. exd5 b3 29. Qd2 Ke7 30. Bf3 Bd7 31.
Rd1 Qd6 32. Qe3 Rb8 33. Ra1 Rb4 34. Be2 Qb6 35. Qf3 a3 36. Rxa3 Ra4 37. Rxa4
Nxa4 38. Bd1 Nc5 39. Qe3 Qb4 40. Qe2 Na4 41. Ng2 Nc5 42. Ne3 Kd6 43. Qf2 Ne4
44. Qg2 Nc5 45. Bxh5 Ke7 46. d6+ Kxd6 47. Bxf7 Qa5 48. h4 Bc6 49. Bd5 Bd7 50.
h5 Qd8 51. Qd2 Qh8 52. Bf3+ Ke7 53. Nd5+ Kf8 54. Qb4 Kg7 55. Qxc5 {1-0
Nakamura,H-Martinez Alcantara,J/chess.com INT 2021}) (12. Be3 Nbd7 $15) 12...
Na6 $3 $15 {The point - a strong computer suggestion.} 13. Nxe7 (13. cxb4 $2
Nxd5 $3 14. Qxd5 Nxb4 15. Qxa8 Nc2+ 16. Kf1 Nxa1 17. Qd5 O-O (17... Nc2 $4 18.
Qc6+) 18. Qd1 Be6 $17 {White obviously faces problems due to his king
placement.}) 13... Qxe7 $15 {If cxb4 at any moment now, both recaptures
guarantee Black a nice game, but perhaps it's better to take with the pawn to
keep the e2-knight at bay.}) (10. O-O $6 Nbd7 11. Be3 O-O 12. a3 (12. a4 b4 13.
Nd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 (14. exd5 a5 $15) 14... Rb8 $15 (14... Nb6 $4 15. Bxb6 Qxb6
16. Qxa8 Bb7 17. a5 $1 $18)) 12... Bb7 $15 (12... Nb6)) (10. a3 $2 Nbd7 $15) (
10. Be3 $6 Nbd7 11. O-O O-O 12. Qd2 Nb6 $132 (12... Rb8 $132)) 10... Nbd7 11.
Nec3 (11. O-O $2 {If White doesn't focus on the centre enough, playing like
this, he can easily get worse.} Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Rb8 (12... Nb6) 13. Be3 h4 14. g4
Bb7 15. Qd2 O-O 16. Nc3 Rc8 17. Rac1 Re8 18. Nd5 Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Nb6 20. Qb7 Nc4
21. Qxa6 Qd7 22. a4 bxa4 23. b3 Nxe3 24. fxe3 Bg5 25. Qd3 Qa7 26. Rce1 a3 27.
c4 a2 28. Kf2 Rb8 29. Ra1 Qa3 30. Qc2 Bxe3+ 31. Ke2 Qxb3 32. Rxa2 Bd4 33. Qxb3
Rxb3 34. Rf3 Rb4 35. Rc2 Ra8 36. Kd2 Ra1 37. Bf1 Rbb1 38. Be2 Bc5 39. Rd3 Bb4+
40. Ke3 Rh1 41. g5 Rxh3+ 42. Kf2 Rh2+ 43. Ke3 Bc5+ 44. Kd2 Rg1 45. Rb3 h3 46.
Rb8+ Kh7 47. Rb3 Kg6 48. Rf3 Rxe2+ 49. Kxe2 h2 {0-1 Abdumalik, Z-Keymer, V/
chess24.com INT 2021}) (11. Nxe7 Qxe7 12. Nc3 Bb7 13. Bg5 Rc8 $132) 11... Nxd5
12. Nxd5 h4 $1 13. g4 (13. Be3 Bb7 $132) 13... Bb7 14. O-O O-O $132 (14... Bxd5
15. Qxd5 (15. exd5 $2 Bg5 $3 $15) 15... O-O 16. c3 Nb6 $132 {0-1 6.h3-e5 7.
Nde2-h5 8.g3-FULL THEORY-PLANS/chess24.com INT 2021}) 15. c3 (15. f4 Bxd5 {
In this scenario, White should always take with the queen. The pawn recapture
is very bad for White.} 16. Qxd5 (16. exd5 $2 exf4 17. Bxf4 Bf6 (17... Bg5 $17
18. Bxd6 $2 Qb6+) 18. c3 Be5 $17 (18... Ne5)) 16... Nb6 $15 {But this is also
significantly better for Black.}) 15... Bxd5 16. Qxd5 (16. exd5 $6 Bg5 $17)
16... Nb6 17. Qd3 Bg5 $3 $15 {Black sacrifices the d-pawn for activity and
dark-squared domination. It's difficult for White to maintain equality.} 18.
Bxg5 Qxg5 19. Qxd6 Nc4 20. Qb4 Rfd8 $17 {Black was already much better.} 21. a4
Rd2 22. Qc5 Rad8 23. axb5 axb5 24. b3 Nb2 25. Qxb5 Nd1 26. Qc5 Qf4 27. b4 R2d3
28. Ra5 Nxc3 29. Qxe5 Qd2 30. Kh1 Ne2 31. Rd5 Nf4 32. Rxd3 Nxd3 33. Qe7 Nxb4
34. Qxh4 Rc8 35. Qg3 Nd3 36. Qf3 Rc3 37. Qf5 Nf4 38. Ra1 Rc1+ 39. Rxc1 Qxc1+
40. Kh2 Qc7 41. Qb5 Ne2+ 42. e5 Nc3 43. Qe8+ Kh7 44. Bf1 Nd5 45. Kg1 Nf4 46.
Qb5 Qc3 47. Kh2 Qf3 48. Qb1+ Kg8 49. Qc2 Ne6 50. Qd2 Nf4 51. Qd8+ Kh7 52. Qh4+
Kg8 53. Qd8+ Kh7 54. Qh4+ Kg8 55. Qg3 Qe4 56. Qc3 Ng6 57. Qc8+ Kh7 58. e6 fxe6
59. Qc3 Nf4 60. Kg3 e5 61. Qe3 Qd5 62. h4 Qh1 63. Qxe5 Qxh4+ 64. Kf3 g5 65.
Qe7+ Kg6 66. Qd6+ Kg7 67. Qe5+ Kg6 68. Qf5+ Kg7 69. Qd7+ Kf6 70. Qd4+ Ke7 71.
Qg7+ Kd6 72. Qf8+ Ke5 73. Qg7+ Kd5 74. Ke3 Qxg4 75. Qd4+ {1/2-1/2 Ochsner,
B-Olsen,F/ Svendborg DEN 2022}) (8. Ng1 $6 {Good enough for blitz but too
romantic to be true!!} b5 $1 9. Nf3 Bb7 10. Ng5 (10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. a4 b4 12. Nd5
Bxd5 13. exd5 Be7 $36 {We are more harmoniously placed and ready to take the
initiative.}) 10... Be7 11. Bd3 $5 (11. a4 $2 b4 12. Bc4 {This tactical idea
can be dealt with easily:} O-O $1 $17 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Nd7
$17 {White is only left with hanging pieces.}) (11. Qf3 $6 {A direct try,
again running into a strong response.} Nc6 $3 $17 {Normally the knight chooses
d7, but here ...Nd4 comes with a strong tempo.} 12. Be3 Nd4 13. Bxd4 exd4 14.
Nd5 Bxd5 15. exd5 Qa5+ $17) (11. a3 $5 {White stops any ...b4. Black will
develop in a classical way without problems:} Nbd7 $132 12. Qf3 Rc8) 11... Nbd7
$132 {Black has moves like ...Rc8, ...0-0, ...Nc5 and ...d5 all available as
possibilities depending on White's choices. In general, the creative but
flawed Ng1 idea has only brought White a position, where he struggles to
maintain full equality.}) 8... Be6 (8... Be7 {is another playable move, but
not my preference.}) 9. Bxf6 {The only logical move... White takes before we
consolidate with ...Nbd7.} (9. f4 Nbd7 10. f5 Bc4 11. Ng3 Rc8 $132 {Black
achieves a good game with standard moves like ...b5, ...Be7 etc.}) (9. Nd5 $6
Bxd5 10. Bxf6 {This seemingly clever continuation runs into a powerful retort.}
(10. exd5 Qa5+ {This check is strong again.} 11. Nc3 Ne4 $17) 10... Qa5+ $3 $17
11. Nc3 Bxe4 $17 {White has lost a full pawn.}) (9. g3 Nbd7 10. Bg2 Be7 11. a4
O-O $132 {The bishop's position on g5 gives us potential ...Nxe4 and ...d5
ideas hanging in the air.}) 9... Qxf6 10. Nd5 Qd8 {Black simply has a very
good position!!... Let's see the lines!} 11. Nec3 (11. Qd3 $6 {White plays for
the long castle, but Black will get much easier attacking chances on the
queenside than White on the opposite flank. The queen also comes under attacks.
} Nd7 (11... g6 $1 {This is also simple and good! See the game Preotu-Theodorou
}) 12. O-O-O g6 13. Kb1 b5 (13... Bh6 {is the alternative:} 14. Nec3 Nc5 15.
Qf3 O-O $132) 14. Nec3 Nc5 15. Qf3 Bg7 $1 $36 {...Rb8-b4 is one simple idea in
Black's hands that is hard to deal with.}) (11. c3 $2 {what to do with the Ne2
now??} g6 12. g3 h4 13. g4 Bh6 $17) (11. a4 Nd7 12. Nec3 Rc8 $1 {Stopping Bc4!}
13. Be2 g6 14. O-O Bh6 $132) 11... g6 $1 {...g6 and ...Bh6 are the most basic
ideas!} 12. Bc4 Bh6 $1 13. O-O O-O 14. a4 Nc6 $1 {Since White does not control
d4 square, let's put the knight there at some moment!} 15. Qd3 Rc8 16. Ba2 Nd4
$36 ({Remeber that you also need to move the king out of the knight checks at
some point. It is possible here immediately:} 16... Kh8 $3 17. Rad1 Nd4 $15) ({
or} 16... Kh7 $3 17. Rad1 Nd4 $15) 17. Rfd1 Kg7 $1 18. Ne3 Qh4 $1 19. Bd5 {
Other moves do not help.} (19. Ncd5 f5 $1 20. exf5 Bxf5 $3 21. Nxf5+ Rxf5 $19)
(19. Bxe6 fxe6 $17) 19... Rc7 20. a5 Kh7 {Black could have played more
forcefully at this point.} (20... Bf4 $1) (20... Rc5 $1) (20... Bxe3 $6 21.
fxe3 Nc6 22. Qe2 $132) 21. Nc4 Rfc8 22. b3 (22. Nxd6 $2 {loses by force:} Rxc3
23. bxc3 Rxc3 24. Qf1 Rxh3 25. gxh3 Nf3+ 26. Kh1 Bxh3 $19) 22... Bf4 23. Ra4
Bg4 $1 24. Qf1 Nf3+ 25. Kh1 Nd2 26. Rxd2 Bxd2 {Black was winning, but White
somehow held his own.} 27. Ne2 Bh6 28. Rb4 Rb8 29. Rb6 Bf8 30. Nc3 Kg7 31. Kg1
Bd7 32. Qd3 Qg5 33. Nxd6 Qc1+ 34. Kh2 Qf4+ 35. Kg1 Bxd6 36. Rxd6 Bb5 37. Nxb5
axb5 38. g3 Qc1+ 39. Kg2 Qa3 40. Rb6 Qxa5 41. Rxb5 Qc3 42. Bc4 Qxd3 43. cxd3
Re7 44. f4 f6 45. Kf3 Ra8 46. Bd5 Ra2 47. h4 Rd2 48. Bc4 Rd1 49. Ke2 Rh1 50.
fxe5 fxe5 51. Rb6 Rh2+ 52. Ke3 Rg2 53. Kf3 Rd2 54. b4 Kh6 55. b5 Re8 56. Rf6
Re7 57. Rf8 Kg7 58. Rg8+ Kh6 59. Rc8 Rb2 60. Rd8 Kg7 61. Rd6 Kh6 62. Rd8 Kg7
63. Rb8 Kh6 64. Rc8 Kg7 65. Rc5 Kh6 66. Ke3 Rg2 67. Kf3 Rb2 68. Rc8 Kg7 69.
Rg8+ Kh6 70. Rd8 Kg7 71. Rd6 Kh6 72. Rb6 Rd2 73. Ke3 Rg2 74. Kf3 Rd2 75. Ke3
Rg2 {1/2-1/2 Abdusattorov, N-Banikas,H/Batumi 2018/[ 0-1 6.h3-e5 7.Nd2-h5 8.
Bg5/Sibenik CRO 2012} *

