-61,-53,-53,-80,-93,-93,-100,-131,-159,-159,-201,-191,-337,-246,-246,-191,-567,
-573,-573]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 e5 7.
Nde2 h5 8. Bg5 Be6 9. Ng3 {Rare and not good.} (9. Qd2 {If White goes for the
long castle-like, this, Black gets excellent queenside prospects and White has
no real activity on the kingside:} Nbd7 10. O-O-O Be7 11. Ng3 g6 $15) 9... g6
10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. Nd5 Qd8 12. Bc4 (12. c3 $2 {If White plays slow chess in
this manner, Black easily gets the upper hand.} Nd7 13. a4 Rc8 14. Bd3 (14. Be2
Bh6 $17) 14... Bxd5 $17) 12... Nd7 13. Nf1 Rc8 14. Nfe3 {White has acquired
what is typically called "superfluous knights". Both of them strive for the
same square, d5. All White's pieces other than the d5-knight are waiting for
their term to play. Black will play around the d5-knight successfully.} Bh6 15.
Bb3 (15. a3 $4 Bxe3 16. Nxe3 (16. fxe3 Rxc4 $19) 16... Bxc4 $19) 15... O-O 16.
c3 Kg7 $1 {This is the right way to avoid potentially discovered checks with
the knight in the future. Believe me, even if you play many moves to cover the
e7 and f6 squares against the check, you can run into it eventually. It is
best to deprive White of his latent tactical potential once and for all.} 17.
Qf3 (17. O-O Qh4 $15) 17... Nf6 (17... Nc5 {would be my preferred square for
the knight.}) 18. Rd1 Nh7 {Black has a good game. White now lashes out with
g2-g4 and immediately runs into trouble.} 19. g4 $6 Qh4 20. Rg1 $2 Bxe3 21.
Qxe3 hxg4 22. hxg4 Bxg4 $19 23. Rd3 Be6 24. Nb6 Rc6 25. Bd5 Bxd5 26. Nxd5 Rc4
27. Kd2 Rxe4 28. Qb6 Rd4 29. Rxg6+ fxg6 30. cxd4 Qxf2+ 31. Kd1 Qf1+ 32. Kc2 0-1

