-125,-201,-218,-224,-187,-211,-230,-146,-114,-84,-198,-205,-208,-219,-208,-208,
-228,-228,-310,-310,-719,-731]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5.
Nc3 a6 6. h3 e5 7. Nde2 h5 8. g3 b5 (8... Be7 9. Bg2 b5 {is a bit more
accurate.}) 9. Nd5 (9. Bg2 {would be inaccurate, because Black can achieve the
desired ...b5, ...Nbd7 set-up.} Nbd7 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. Qxd5 (11. exd5) 11... Rb8
(11... Nb6)) 9... Nbd7 10. Nxf6+ $6 ({White should have played} 10. Nec3 {
, quickly transposing to our main line.} Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Be7 12. Bg2 h4 13. g4
Bb7 14. O-O O-O) 10... Nxf6 11. Bg5 Bb7 {Black has no problems at all.} 12. Nc3
Be7 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. a4 b4 15. Nd5 Rc8 $3 {Black stops Bc4 and introduces the
idea of ...Rc5!} 16. h4 (16. b3 h4 17. g4 Bg5 18. Bc4 O-O $11 {with a dynamic
equality.}) 16... Rc5 $3 {And with this great manoeuver all of a sudden Black
is better !!} 17. Nxf6+ ({In the case of} 17. Bg2 $6 {, we of course take on d5
with a favourable structure transformation:} Bxd5 18. exd5 a5 19. O-O g6 20.
Qd3 O-O $17 {White's position is almost hopeless because of the difference in
effectiveness of the opposite-coloured bishops!}) 17... Qxf6 18. Bg2 O-O 19.
O-O Rfc8 20. Rc1 a5 $1 {Don't forget to play this consolidating move at some
point.} 21. c3 g6 22. Qd2 bxc3 23. Rxc3 Rxc3 24. bxc3 Rc5 $17 {White has
numerous weaknesses. Black is better. He went on to win after some
complications.} 25. Rb1 Bc6 26. Qh6 Qd8 27. g4 Qf8 28. Qg5 hxg4 29. h5 Kg7 30.
Qxg4 Rxc3 31. Bf3 Qe7 32. hxg6 fxg6 33. Rb8 Bd7 34. Qg3 Be6 35. Kg2 Rc8 36. Rb6
Rc4 37. Rb8 Rxa4 38. Bh5 Bf7 39. Bg4 Rb4 40. Ra8 Rxe4 41. Qh3 Rxg4+ 0-1

