{[%evp 0,150,27,11,57,57,68,55,55,32,45,37,68,32,32,5,44,45,45,16,16,14,28,14,
14,9,-4,0,0,0,-5,8,-7,-16,-14,-44,-41,-26,-19,-19,-29,-96,-10,-4,60,-5,37,-27,
-58,-163,-111,-179,-113,-113,-113,-127,-127,-97,-97,-97,-91,-92,-99,-99,-119,
-119,-119,-108,-119,-119,-119,-119,-53,-53,-52,-25,-29,-101,-101,-101,-101,
-100,-100,-100,-77,-73,-75,-77,-61,-61,-58,-54,-36,-36,-29,-30,-30,-58,-40,-41,
-34,-34,-34,-34,-36,-39,-36,-36,-32,-32,-35,-30,-33,-30,-29,-28,-28,-28,-28,
-62,-28,-28,-28,-28,-28,-28,-28,-28,-28,-67,-28,-67,-67,-67,-67,-67,-67,-62,
-28,-28,-28,-28,-28,-28,-28,-33,-29,-28,-29,-28,-29,-28,-29] A great game by
Black... and a narrow escape by the young superstar with the white pieces!!} 1.
e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. h3 ({In the line} 6. g3 e5
7. Nde2 Be7 8. h3 {White is a tempo down with his plan compared to the game.})
6... e5 7. Nde2 h5 8. Bg5 Be6 9. Bxf6 (9. f4 {With the knight on b3, we would
react by taking on f4. Now, however, we have the c4-square for the bishop and
f4-f5 is not a real threat:} Nbd7 10. f5 Bc4 {Followed by ...Be7, ...Rc8, ...
b5 etc. with typical Najdorf play.}) (9. Nd5 Nbd7) 9... Qxf6 10. Nd5 Qd8 11.
Nec3 {White's knights connect very early, but leave the d4-square, which will
be occupied by Black with his knight, instead of going for ...Nd7.} g6 ({After
} 11... Nd7 {White needs to put the bishop on c4:} 12. Bc4 ({A move like} 12.
a4 $6 {runs into} Rc8 $1 {The rook takes the c4-square away from the bishop
and it will have to be deployed passively, giving Black a satisfactory game:}
13. Be2 g6 14. O-O Bh6 $11) 12... Rc8 (12... Nb6 $2 13. Nxb6 Qxb6 14. Bb3 $16 {
with control over the d5-square and one unnecessary knight gone off the board
for White.}) 13. Bb3 Nc5 $14 {The knight is less effective than in the game
and White has some advantage.}) 12. Bc4 Bh6 13. O-O O-O 14. a4 Nc6 $1 {As
mentioned earlier, I like this move very much. Black directs the knight to d4.}
15. Qd3 Rc8 16. Ba2 Nd4 {White cannot move his knight from c3 to make way for
c2-c3, because the c2-pawn is hanging.} 17. Rfd1 {White already doesn't really
know what to do. He plays "normal" moves that don't achieve much.} Kg7 $1 {
Typically we want to step out of any potential checks by the d5-knight to
deprive White of any unexpected tactical possibilities.} 18. Ne3 Qh4 $1 {
It is always a strategic luxury when we can safely place our queen close to
the opponent's king.} 19. Bd5 ({If} 19. Ncd5 {White is threatening to play c3,
but runs into} f5 $1 20. exf5 Bxf5 $3 21. Nxf5+ Rxf5 $19) (19. Bxe6 fxe6 $17)
19... Rc7 ({In a blitz game I wouldn't be able to resist playing the} 19... Rc6
$5 {sacrifice. But it is objectively dubious.}) 20. a5 Kh7 {There were more
substantial options possible here.} (20... Bf4 $1) (20... Rc5 $1) (20... Bxe3
$6 21. fxe3 Nc6 22. Qe2 $132) 21. Nc4 Rfc8 (21... Bf4 $1 {immediately was
better.}) 22. b3 (22. Nxd6 $2 Rxc3 23. bxc3 Rxc3 24. Qf1 Rxh3 $1 25. gxh3 Nf3+
26. Kh1 Bxh3 $19) 22... Bf4 23. Ra4 $2 ({White should have gone for} 23. Bxe6
$1 fxe6 24. Ne2 $11 {, suddenly equalizing.}) 23... Bg4 $1 24. Qf1 Nf3+ 25. Kh1
Nd2 26. Rxd2 Bxd2 $17 {Black has won the exchange and should be close to
winning. Nevertheless, White fought very hard and held a draw.} 27. Ne2 Bh6 28.
Rb4 Rb8 29. Rb6 Bf8 30. Nc3 Kg7 31. Kg1 Bd7 32. Qd3 Qg5 33. Nxd6 Qc1+ 34. Kh2
Qf4+ 35. Kg1 Bxd6 36. Rxd6 Bb5 37. Nxb5 axb5 38. g3 Qc1+ 39. Kg2 Qa3 40. Rb6
Qxa5 41. Rxb5 Qc3 42. Bc4 Qxd3 43. cxd3 Re7 44. f4 f6 45. Kf3 Ra8 46. Bd5 Ra2
47. h4 Rd2 48. Bc4 Rd1 49. Ke2 Rh1 50. fxe5 fxe5 51. Rb6 Rh2+ 52. Ke3 Rg2 53.
Kf3 Rd2 54. b4 Kh6 55. b5 Re8 56. Rf6 Re7 57. Rf8 Kg7 58. Rg8+ Kh6 59. Rc8 Rb2
60. Rd8 Kg7 61. Rd6 Kh6 62. Rd8 Kg7 63. Rb8 Kh6 64. Rc8 Kg7 65. Rc5 Kh6 66. Ke3
Rg2 67. Kf3 Rb2 68. Rc8 Kg7 69. Rg8+ Kh6 70. Rd8 Kg7 71. Rd6 Kh6 72. Rb6 Rd2
73. Ke3 Rg2 74. Kf3 Rd2 75. Ke3 Rg2 1/2-1/2

