[White "LECTURE 5"]
[Black "INTRODUCTION"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "13"]
[EventDate "2023.10.06"]
[SourceVersionDate "2023.10.06"]

{The starting position of this lecture is being reached after} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 {This aggressive line used to be
very popular a few decades ago. Nowadays modern engines have shown several
good ways to play against it. The vast majority of games in this line continue
with} e6 7. Bb3 {White plays 7.Bb3 almost exclusively with the exception of
some harmless sidelines (we cover them). The bishop is almost always going to
end on b3, while White hasn't decided on whether to play Be3 or Bg5, or
whether to castle long or short. An opening move that is certain, should be
played. This is a strategically risky position for White. He will be doing
fine if the b3-bishop can be included in the game by means of f2-f4 followed
by f4-f5 or e4-e5 at a good moment in combination with sacrifices on e6 or f7.
If Black can consolidate the position the bishop will be isolated on b3 and
might even be captured. On the other hand Black's light-squared bishop on b7
will be unopposed. In short: the evaluation of the position depends on White's
abilty to include the b3-bishop in the game and Black's chances to prevent
this. Here we will see that with the help of engines Black manages to
neutralize White's initiative and can take over in many lines.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.Bc4"]
[Black "Theoretical Review"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "28"]
[EventDate "2023.10.07"]
[SourceVersionDate "2023.10.06"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bc4 {This aggressive
line used to be very popular a few decades ago. Nowadays modern engines have
shown several good ways to play against it.} e6 7. Bb3 {[%csl Rb3] White plays
7.Bb3 almost exclusively with the exception of some harmless sidelines. The
bishop is almost always going to end on b3, while White hasn't decided on
whether to play Be3 or Bg5, or whether to castle long or short. An opening
move that is certain, should be played. This is a strategically risky position
for White. White will be doing fine if the b3-bishop can be included in the
game by means of f2-f4 followed by f4-f5 or e4-e5 at a good moment in
combination with sacrifices on e6 or f7. If Black can consolidate the position
the bishop will be isolated on b3 and might even be captured. On the other
hand, Black's light-squared bishop on b7 will be unopposed. In short: the
evaluation of the position depends on White's ability to include the b3-bishop
in the game and Black's chances to prevent this. Here we will see that with
the help of engines, Black manages to neutralize White's initiative and can
take over in many lines.} (7. f3 $5 b5 8. Bb3 {transposes to 7.Bb3-b5 8.f3.}) (
7. a4 {Not much theoretical knowledge is needed here.} Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Ba2 {
Usually White will play something like this after which Black gets a good
position after} (9. Kh1 {Here Black has an instructive plan which you need to
keep in mind.} Nxe4 10. Nxe4 d5 11. Bd3 dxe4 12. Bxe4 f5 $1 13. Bf3 e5 {
[%csl Ge5,Gf5]} 14. Nb3 {and Black has several choices to claim an advantage.}
Qc7 $36 (14... e4) (14... Nd7)) 9... Nc6 10. Be3 Bd7 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gd7c6]
intending to take on d4 and put a bishop on c6.} 11. f4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bc6 13.
Qe2 b5 $36) (7. Be3 $5 {is rare but interesting.} b5 8. Bb3 Be7 (8... Bb7 $6 {
It is important not to play this move leaving e6 undefended, White has two
great options to pose problems for Black. This is an example of White getting
the b3-bishop included in the attack.} 9. O-O Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. f4 {
[%csl Gb3][%cal Gf4f5]} (11. Qg4 Bb7 12. Rae1 {[%csl Gb3,Re6,Re8,Rf7][%cal
Gd4e6,Gb3e6]})) 9. Qf3 b4 $1 (9... Bb7 $4 {Another example of ignoring White's
chances to sacrifice on e6.} 10. Bxe6 $18 {As a general rule in the Sicilian:
if White can get three pawns for a sacrificed piece, White will be much better
or even win.}) (9... Qc7 $1 {is also possible.} 10. e5 $2 (10. Qg3 O-O 11. a3
Nc6 $132 (11... Re8 $132)) 10... Bb7 11. exd6 Bxd6 12. Qh3 O-O $15 13. O-O-O
Be5 $15) 10. Nce2 Qc7 11. O-O O-O $132 12. e5 dxe5 13. Qxa8 exd4 14. Nxd4 Bb7
15. Qa7 Ng4 16. g3 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Bc5 $19 {winning the queen.}) (7. O-O b5 8.
Bb3 Be7 $1 {transposes to 7.Bb3-b5 8.0-0-Be7}) 7... b5 {[%cal Gf8e7] In this
starting position White's most important idea is connected with Qf3. There are
three versions of this idea: 1) 8. Qf3 right away. 2) 8. Bg5 and 9.Qf3,
normally combined with long castle. 3) 8.0-0 and 9.Qf3} 8. O-O $5 (8. Be3 {
transposes to 7.Be3!?-b5 8.Bb3}) (8. f3 $5 Nbd7 9. O-O (9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Nxe6
Qb6 $17 {With White having only two pawns for the piece, there is not enough
compensation.}) (9. Be3 Nc5 $5 10. Qd2 Bd7 11. O-O-O Qb8 {[%cal Yb8b5,Ga6a5,
Ga5a4]} (11... Qc8 $5) 12. g4 a5 13. g5 Nh5 $36 14. Nde2 {[%cal Yd2d7,Ge3c5]}
Qc8 $1 $17 {[%cal Yc8d7,Ga5a4]}) (9. a3 Nc5 10. Ba2 Qc7 11. Be3 Be7 $11) 9...
Nc5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Yc5e6,Yc5b3] defending and attacking at the same time.
Black might continue with ...Qc7 of ...Bb7. Be careful not to play ...Be7
first allowing Nc6.} 10. Kh1 Bb7 11. Be3 Be7 12. Qe2 O-O 13. Rad1 Qc7 $17 {
leaves White with no (active) plan.}) (8. Qf3 $6 {This move was fashionable in
the past ..but 8...Bb7! is very good. In modern times this move is considered
inaccurate.} Bb7 $3 {[%cal Gb8c6] intending either b4 or Nc6. To make things
easy we're going to play the set-up with Nc6 most of the time, even when the
engine might prefer putting the b8-knight on d7.} 9. O-O (9. Qh3 Nc6 10. Be3
Na5 $36 (10... Nxd4 {also offer Black a good game.} 11. Bxd4 Be7)) (9. a3 {
is the computer's choice.} Nc6 10. Nxc6 Bxc6 $13 11. O-O Be7 12. Qg3 O-O 13.
Bh6 Ne8 14. Rad1 Bh4 $1 {is a move the computer likes very much. The h4-bishop
will land on f6 and after chasing the h6-bishop away by Kh8, Black can
continue with Be7 or Be5. Here it becomes clear why 14.Bh4 was included: The
knight on e8 will join the game with tempo on f6 by hitting the g4-queen.} (
14... a5 $132) (14... Qc7 {is also a decent move and shows an important rule
for Black.} 15. Rfe1 Kh8 16. Bg5 Bxg5 $1 {This is it, Black is happy to
exchange the black-squared bishops. Generally, all exchanges except for the
b3-bishop are favorable.}) 15. Qg4 Bf6 $1 16. Rfe1 Qc7 $15 17. Bc1 Qb7 18. f3
Be5 (18... a5)) (9. Bg5 b4 $3 {is an idea we should always keep in mind. The
point is to chase the knight away from the centre. Instead of collecting pawns
we further consolidate our position and play against the 'isolated' b3-bishop.}
(9... Nc6 $5) (9... Be7 $2 10. Bxe6 {Again, do not fall for this!}) 10. Ba4+ $2
(10. Na4 Nbd7 11. O-O-O Qa5 $15) (10. Nce2 Nbd7 11. O-O-O Nc5 $17 12. Bxf6 Qxf6
13. Qxf6 gxf6 14. f3 h5 $15 {with a nice endgame for Black.}) 10... Nbd7 11.
Bxf6 (11. Nce2 Qa5 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 $17) 11... Qxf6 12. Bxd7+ Kxd7 13. Qxf6 gxf6
$17 14. Na4 Rb8 $17) 9... Nc6 $1 10. Nxc6 (10. e5 $2 {loses by force.} Nxd4 11.
Qxb7 Rb8 12. Qxa6 Rb6 13. Qa5 Nc6 14. Qxb6 Qxb6 15. exf6 gxf6 $19 {and White
is just a queen down for no compensation.}) 10... Bxc6 11. Re1 Be7 {[%cal
Ge8g8]} 12. Qg3 O-O 13. Bh6 {is a typical move.} ({After a quite move like} 13.
f3 {we have reached the ultimate goal in the 6.Bc4 Najdorf which is to get a
relatively quite position where White can make no good use of the b3-Bishop.
Black can now consolidate the position and take over the initiative.} Qc7 14.
Be3 b4 15. Ne2 a5 16. Nd4 Bd7 {[%cal Yd7e6] protecting against Bxe6 and
threatening a5-a4.} 17. Bh6 Ne8 $15 {[%cal Ga5a4]}) 13... Ne8 14. a3 Kh8 15.
Be3 Nf6 16. f3 Qc7 $132 {[%cal Ga6a5] and Black is on the positive side of
equality.}) (8. f4 $6 {is premature, Black is better after concrete play.} Bb7
9. e5 (9. f5 e5 10. Nf3 Be7 11. Bg5 Nbd7 $15) 9... dxe5 10. fxe5 Nfd7 11. Qh5 (
11. O-O {with all kinds of ideas to sacrifice on e6 or f7. Black ignores the
hanging pawn and finishes development, isolating the b3-bishop from the game.}
Bc5 12. Kh1 O-O $15 {[%csl Rb3] Black has reached the most urgent goal having
avoided all sacrifices. Now we can start thinking about Bxd4 followed by Nc6
and collect the e5 pawn.}) 11... g6 12. Qh3 Nc6 $1 13. Nxc6 Bxc6 14. O-O Qe7 $3
15. Bf4 Bg7 $17 {[%csl Rb3]}) (8. Bg5 $1 {is a very aggressive move, but
objectively black is doing great!} Be7 9. Qf3 (9. O-O O-O 10. Qf3 Qb6 11. Rad1
Qb7) 9... Qb6 $1 {is the most practical solution. The idea is to play Qb7 if
necessary and to counter e4-e5 with Bb7.} (9... Ra7 {Engines even suggest this
move as totally acceptable.}) 10. O-O-O (10. e5 $2 Bb7 $17) (10. Be3 Qb7 $1 $15
) (10. O-O $6 Nbd7 (10... Qxd4 $2 11. e5 $18) 11. Rad1 O-O $15 12. Qg3 (12.
Rfe1 Nc5 $15 13. Bd5 Bb7 $15) 12... Nh5 13. Qh4 Bxg5 14. Qxg5 Nhf6 15. Rfe1 Nc5
$15) 10... O-O $1 (10... Bb7 $4 {is a blunder and allows White to show a nice
motive:} 11. Be3 $1 {luring the queen to c7 or d8 when the Bxe6-sacrifice is
going to be even stronger.} (11. Bxe6 {is also interesting.} fxe6 12. Nxe6 $16
Kf7 13. Nd5) 11... Qc7 12. Bxe6 $18) 11. Rhe1 (11. Kb1 Bb7 $1 {Once we're
castled we do not fear Bex6 anymore.} (11... Nbd7 $1 12. Qg3 Nc5 $36) 12. Qg3 (
12. Be3 Qc7 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Nxe6 Qc4 15. Nxf8 Bxf8 $15 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7e5]
is double-edged, but Black has very active pieces and should be better.}) 12...
Nc6 13. Be3 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Qc7 $132 15. e5 dxe5 16. Bxe5 Qc6 $15 {and Black has
consolidated. White will start to feel the problems surrounding the b3-bishop.}
) (11. e5 $2 dxe5 $17 12. Nxe6 Bxe6 $19) (11. Qg3 $5 Nbd7 $1 (11... Bb7 $4 12.
Be3 Qc7 13. Bxe6 $18 {ALWAYS be aware of this trick!}) (11... Bd7 $1 12. Bh6 (
12. Rhe1 b4 $11) 12... Ne8 13. f4 Kh8 $132) 12. Rhe1 Nc5 $15) 11... Bb7 $1 12.
Qg3 (12. Qh3 Nc6 $1 13. Nxc6 (13. Nxe6 $2 fxe6 14. Bxe6+ Kh8 15. Bf5 Bc8 $3 16.
Bxf6 Bxf5 17. Bxg7+ Kxg7 18. exf5 Qxf2 $15) 13... Bxc6 $14) 12... Nc6 13. Nxc6
(13. Be3 Qc7 $132) 13... Bxc6 14. Nd5 (14. Bxf6 $2 Bxf6 15. Rxd6 Be7 16. Rd2 a5
$17) 14... Bxd5 15. exd5 e5 $36 16. Be3 (16. f4 Nh5 $17) (16. Bh6 Nh5 17. Qg4
Qxf2 $3 18. Qxh5 gxh6 19. Rf1 Qh4 $15 20. Qf5 Qg5+) 16... Qd8 $1 $36) 8... Be7
$1 {Just to be able to castle fast!} 9. Qf3 (9. Be3 Bd7 $5 10. f4 b4 11. Na4 (
11. Nce2 O-O 12. Qd3 Nc6 $13) 11... O-O 12. f5 e5 13. Nf3 Bb5 14. Nb6 Bxf1 15.
Qxf1 Nbd7 16. Nxa8 Qxa8 $15) (9. Re1 $5 Bd7 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] more of the same!
It really is an idea-based opening.} 10. Qf3 Nc6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Qg3 (12. a3
O-O 13. Bf4 Qc7 14. Rad1 Rad8 15. Ba2 Qb7 $15 (15... Bb7 $13)) 12... O-O 13.
Bh6 Ne8 14. Rad1 b4 15. Nb1 Bh4 16. Qg4 Bxf2+ 17. Kxf2 Qf6+ 18. Bf4 e5 $15 {
is a nice computer tactic to remember.}) (9. a3 O-O 10. Qf3 Bb7 {We're not
fearing Bxe6 anymore.} (10... Qb6 {is also possible.} 11. Be3 Qb7 {[%cal Gc8d7,
Gb8c6]} 12. Rfe1 {and here again we play our typical idea: Bd7 followed by Nc6.
} Bd7 13. Qg3 Nc6 14. Bh6 Ne8 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Rad1 Kh8 17. Bc1 Nf6 18. f3 a5
$15 {and the initiative is Black's.}) 11. Qg3 Nc6 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Bh6 Ne8 14.
Rad1 Bh4 $1 (14... a5 $15 {also gives the advantage to Black.}) 15. Qg4 Bf6 $15
16. Rfe1 Qc7 $15 {[%cal Gg8h8,Gf6e5,Gf6e7,Ge8f6]}) (9. f4 $6 {This is better
for black if he has done his homework! This is also one of the few lines where
memorization of concrete lines is important.} Bb7 $3 10. e5 (10. Bxe6 $6 fxe6
11. Nxe6 Qb6+ 12. Kh1 Nxe4 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. Qxd5 Qc6 15. Nxg7+ (15. Re1 $2 Qxd5
$3 16. Nc7+ Kd8 $3 17. Nxd5 Nf6 $3 18. Rxe7 Nxd5 19. Rxg7 Nd7 $19 {Tigran
Petrosian-Papaioannou Plovdiv 2008 (0-1)}) 15... Kd8 16. Qf5 Nd7 17. Ne6+ Kc8
18. Nd4 Qb7 19. Be3 (19. Re1 Nf2+ 20. Kg1 Rg8 $15) 19... Bf6 20. a4 Rf8 $17 (
20... b4 $15) 21. Ne6 Rg8 $17) 10... dxe5 11. fxe5 Bc5 12. Be3 Nc6 13. exf6
Bxd4 14. Qe2 (14. fxg7 Bxe3+ 15. Kh1 Rg8 16. Bxe6 (16. Qh5 Rxg7 17. Bxe6 (17.
Rxf7 Rxf7 18. Bxe6 Qf6 19. Nd5 Qg6 20. Bxf7+ Qxf7 21. Qxf7+ Kxf7 22. Nxe3 Rd8
$19) 17... Ne5 18. Bd5 Rg5 19. Qd1 Bxd5 20. Nxd5 Ng4 $1 21. Nxe3 Nxe3 22. Qe2
Re5 23. Rf3 Qe7 $19) 16... Rxg7 17. Bxf7+ $5 (17. Qf3 Qe7 18. Nd5 (18. Bd5 Nd4
19. Qxe3 (19. Qh3 Bd2 20. Bxb7 Qxb7 21. Rf2 Bg5 22. Re1+ Ne6 23. Ne4 O-O-O $17)
19... Qxe3 20. Rae1 Bxd5 21. Rxe3+ Be6 $19) 18... Nd4 19. Bxf7+ Rxf7 20. Nc7+
Qxc7 21. Qxe3+ Kf8 22. Qxd4 Kg8 $19) 17... Rxf7 18. Qh5 Ne5 $1 19. Qxe5+ Qe7
20. Qh5 Kf8 21. Qxh7 (21. Rae1 $2 Rxf1+ 22. Rxf1+ Kg7 $1 23. Nd5 Bxd5 24. Qxd5
Re8 $19) 21... Bd4 22. Rae1 (22. Ne4 Bd5 $1 23. c3 Bg7 24. Ng3 Rd8 25. Rxf7+
Bxf7 $17) 22... Re8 $3 23. h3 Bg7 24. Qh5 Kg8 25. Nd5 Rxf1+ 26. Rxf1 Qd7 $17)
14... Bxe3+ 15. Qxe3 Qd4 16. Qxd4 Nxd4 17. Rad1 Nxb3 18. fxg7 Rg8 19. axb3 Rxg7
$15) 9... Qb6 $1 10. Be3 (10. Bg5 $6 O-O (10... Qxd4 $2 11. e5 $16) 11. Rad1
Nbd7 12. Rfe1 Bb7 13. Qg3 Nh5 14. Qh4 Bxg5 15. Qxg5 Nhf6 $15 16. Re3 h6 17. Qh4
Ne5 $17) 10... Qb7 $1 {protecting everything.} 11. Qg3 (11. a3 O-O 12. Rfe1 Nc6
{Always check the e5 tactics before playing moves like this, here they don't
work of course.} (12... Bd7 {following our standard scheme is also very good.})
13. Nxc6 Qxc6 $132 {with typical play} 14. Rad1 Bb7 15. Qg3 Rfe8 $1 $132 {
is a smart move! The rook offers some extra protection to the e6-pawn,
anticipating f2-f4-f5, and evacuates the f8-square for the bishop to protect
against mate after Bh6. Also ...g6 is possible now.} (15... Nh5 16. Qh3 Nf6 $11
{is a typical engine draw after 17.Qg3.})) 11... b4 $1 {kicking the knight
away!} 12. Na4 Nbd7 (12... O-O {will transpose.}) 13. f3 (13. Qxg7 $6 {
Grabbing the pawn is too dangerous for White, Black obtains excellent
compensation after} Rg8 14. Qh6 Ng4 $3 15. Qf4 Ndf6 $3 $36 16. Qf3 Bd7 $15 {
where White is under pressure.}) 13... O-O $132 14. Rfe1 {and Black has many
options, all of which are ideas we've already seen. Black has successfully
killed White's active play and has isolated the bishop on b3. Black can
already dream of taking over and playing for a win.} (14. Rad1 Ne5 $132 {
[%cal Ge5g6] is a personal favourite.} (14... a5 $132)) 14... Ne5 $132 (14...
a5 $132) (14... Re8 $132) (14... Rb8 15. c4 bxc3 16. Nxc3 Ne5 $132) *

