{The final lecture is dedicated to arguably the most dangerous system in the
Najdorf - the dreaded 6.Bg5. After the moves} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 {, our choice is going to be} Nbd7 {This flexible
continuation is very practical. In this line, the theoretical overload is
considerably smaller in comparison to all the lines based on 6...e6. Black is
planning to answer the moves 7.f4 and 7.Qe2 with 7...Qa5!. The strongest
continuation 7.Bc4, however, should be met by 7...Qb6. In the arising complex
positions, Black has an excellent counterplay. Besides fresh new ideas, in
this lecture, you will also see very deep concepts. Hopefully, all the
theoretical analysis provided here will convince you that we can keep
everything under control against 6.Bg5.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.Bg5 Nbd7 7.Qe2"]
[Black "Theoretical Review"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "26"]
[EventDate "2023.10.07"]
[SourceVersionDate "2023.10.06"]

{[%evp 0,26,24,31,52,66,79,48,49,31,33,33,58,53,54,39,66,33,56,58,61,51,70,60,
53,36,36,33,25]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5
Nbd7 7. Qe2 $1 {So big is White's desire to put his queen on a light square,
that he is even willing to block his Bf1!... just imagine how good it would be
for White to have it on c4! For example, 7.Bc4 Qc7? 8.Qe2!... but 7.Bc4 Qb6
prevents it!!} Qa5 $1 {SOS!! Another quite rare... but very interesting line!}
8. Bd2 $5 {The suggestion of Parimarjan Negi PLEASE NOTE THAT 8.h4 h6 9.Bd2 IS
DIFFERENT THAN 8.Bd2} (8. f4 $2 {SUPER SOS!!! Once again this happens to be
wrong!... and still many White players will not know it... and they will get a
worse game immediately!} h6 $1 9. Bh4 (9. Bxf6 Nxf6 10. f5 {PERHAPS THIS IS
THE ONLY MOVE FOR WHITE... NOT TO BE WORSE!} (10. O-O-O $2 Bg4 $1 11. Nf3 Rc8
$3 {...Rxc3! is a big idea.} (11... e5 $1 $15 {Also simple and good!}) 12. e5
Rxc3 13. exf6 (13. bxc3 Nd5 $15) 13... Rc7 $15) (10. Nb3 Qc7 11. e5 $2 {
Aggressive, but it only leads to overextension. Black has the important ...Bg4
tempo.} (11. f5 {is not so satisfactory with the knight on b3.} e6 $15 (11...
g5 $5 $15)) 11... dxe5 12. fxe5 Bg4 13. Qe3 Nd7 $15 {It's hard for White to
keep everything together.} 14. h3 (14. Nd5 Qc6 $1 15. Nb4 (15. Nf4 g5 16. Nd3
Bg7 $17) 15... Qb6 16. Qxb6 Nxb6 $15 {The attacks against the queen haven't
brought White much.}) 14... Be6 $15) (10. e5 $2 Nd5 11. Nb3 Nxc3 12. Nxa5 Nxe2
13. Bxe2 dxe5 14. fxe5 g6 $15 {White has a significant weakness on e5 and
Black has the bishop pair.}) 10... g5 $1 $132 {A typical positional idea.
Black threatens to grab a lot of queenside space and prepares ...Bg7, so White
should rather take en passant.} 11. fxg6 fxg6 12. O-O-O Bg4 (12... Bg7 $11) 13.
Nf3 h5 $5 {Introducing the ...Bh6+ idea.} 14. Kb1 Rc8 $11 {The position
demands more from White than from Black, whose long-range pieces work
perfectly.}) (9. Nb3 Qc7 10. Bh4 e5 $15 11. fxe5 (11. f5 b5) 11... dxe5 12. Qc4
Qxc4 13. Bxc4 Nb6 14. Bd3 Be6 $15 15. O-O-O Bb4 $15 (15... Rc8 $15)) 9... e5 $1
10. Nb3 (10. Nf5 $2 g6 11. Ne3 Nxe4 12. Nc4 Nxc3 $17) (10. fxe5 dxe5 11. Nb3 (
11. Nf5 $2 {White overshoots the mark.} g6 12. Ng3 (12. Ne3 Nxe4 13. Nc4 Nxc3
14. Nxa5 Nxe2 15. Kxe2 Be7 $19) 12... Ba3 $19 (12... g5 $19) 13. O-O-O Qxc3)
11... Qc7 12. O-O-O Be7 $15 {Black will start the classical play with ...b5.})
10... Qc7 $36 11. g3 (11. O-O-O exf4 $13) 11... Be7 12. O-O-O b5 13. a3 (13.
Bh3 $2 g5 $3 $17 {There are direct tactical problems with the bishops on the
h-file.} 14. Bxd7+ (14. fxg5 hxg5 15. Bxd7+ Nxd7 16. Nd5 Qd8 {There won't be
even nearly enough compensation for the lost bishop.} 17. Rhf1 (17. Qg4 Nb6 $19
) 17... gxh4 18. Qf3 f6 19. Qc3 Bb7 20. Nc7+ Kf7 21. Nxa8 Qxa8 $19) 14... Nxd7
15. Nd5 Qd8 16. Qd2 {This is quite a clever response. He introduces the Na5
and Qc3 ideas. But Black has an overwhelming retort up his sleeve.} Nf6 $3 $19
{White is lost based on the following forced line:} (16... gxh4 $2 17. Na5 Nb8
18. Qc3 $16) 17. Nxe7 Qxe7 18. fxg5 Nxe4 19. Qe3 hxg5 20. Qxe4 Bb7 21. Qe3 Bxh1
22. Bxg5 f6 $19) (13. Kb1 b4 14. Bxf6 {White has to go for this. 14.Nd5 Nxd5
15.exd5 g5! wins a piece.} Nxf6 15. Nd5 Nxd5 16. exd5 O-O {Black's king is
much safer here. The ...a5-a4 assault will come sooner or later, while on the
other flank, there will be no trace of a comparatively successful attack by
White.} 17. fxe5 dxe5 18. Nd2 a5 19. Nc4 Bd6 $15 {The passed d-pawn is not
enough of an asset to alleviate White's problems fully.}) (13. Bg2 $4 {Not
cautious enough.} b4 14. Bxf6 (14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 g5 $19 {Remember this
idea. The bishop is lost.}) 14... bxc3 15. Bxe7 Kxe7 $17) 13... Rb8 14. Bg2 O-O
$15 {Black is going to be quite effective with his queenside play.}) (8. h4 $5
h6 $1 {We want to avoid passive play like 8...e6?! 9.0-0-0 h6 10.Bxf6! Nxf6 11.
f4 followed by g4 etc. with a big attack for White.} 9. Bd2 (9. Be3 $2 Nxe4 $17
) (9. Bxf6 $2 Nxf6 10. O-O-O h5 $1 $15 {The same idea as in the 9.Bd2 line.} (
10... g6 $5 $36)) 9... Qb6 $1 10. Nb3 h5 $1 $146 {A VERY GOOD NOVELTY! ( It
was found in 2013 by me... not sure if it has ever been played since then)
After 10...h5, both f3-g4 and f4 plans appear to be less attractive... and
that's only because white's pawn is on h4, and these advances cause white
additional weaknesses!} (10... e5 $2 11. g4 $1) 11. O-O-O (11. Nd5 Nxd5 12.
exd5 Nf6 $1 13. Be3 (13. c4 g6 14. Ba5 Qa7 15. Bc3 Bg7 16. Bd4 Qb8 $132 {
Black has great play. e7 is not a serious weakness because of the open
tactical nature of the position, e.g. 17. 0-0-0? 0-0!}) 13... Qc7 14. c4 g6
$132 {Black has an easy game with ...Bg7, ... 0-0, ...Bf5 or ...e6 etc.}) (11.
Bg5 g6 12. Nd5 $6 Nxd5 13. exd5 Ne5 14. O-O-O Bg7 15. f3 O-O $1 $15 {Of course
we sacrifice the e7 pawn! The position is all about activity.} 16. Kb1 (16.
Bxe7 $2 Re8 17. Bg5 Bf5 18. Qd2 Rac8 19. c3 Nc4 20. Bxc4 Rxc4 21. Rhe1 Rec8 $19
) 16... Bd7 $5 $15 (16... Re8 $15)) 11... g6 $1 {Black has very good
counterplay! Here are some sample lines :} (11... e6 $5 {This is another
interesting alternative with typical Najdorf play for both sides.}) 12. Bg5 (
12. f3 Qc7 $3 {this is even more accurate than 12...Bg7 13. g4!} (12... Bg7 13.
g4 $1 $36) 13. Bg5 b5 14. Qd2 Bb7 $15) (12. f4 Qc7 $1 $13 (12... Nc5 $1 $13)
13. Kb1 Bg7 $15 14. f5 b5 $36) (12. Kb1 Bg7 13. f4 Qc7 14. Qe1 b5 15. a3 Bb7
$15 {The scope of the black pieces' influence is larger.}) (12. Nd5 $6 Nxd5 13.
exd5 Bg7 14. Bg5 O-O $17 {White has real issues with unfinished development
and the monster g7-bishop and the e7 pawn is not so relevant.}) 12... Bg7 13.
g3 Qc7 14. Bg2 Nb6 $132 {Black uses the fact that now the c4-square is
unprotected by the bishop. A complex battle is about to begin, e.g.} 15. Rhe1
Nh7 $1 16. e5 $1 {The only good retort.} dxe5 17. Be3 O-O 18. Bxb6 Qxb6 19. Nd5
Qa7 20. Nxe7+ Kh8 $132 {The position remains highly double-edged.}) 8... h5 $5
{The computer's first choice! Nipping White's kingside expansion in the bud is
a really important goal.} (8... g6 $5 {A secondary possibility.} 9. O-O-O b5 $1
10. a3 Qb6 (10... Qc7 11. g4 $1 $16) 11. Be3 Qb7 {This looks similar to the 8..
.h5!? line, but White has the option of 12.g4! so Black has to be careful
going for this line.}) 9. O-O-O (9. Nd5 $6 {In the end, this escapade loses
White some time.} Qd8 10. O-O-O (10. c4 g6 11. f3 Bg7 $132) 10... e5 $3 11.
Nxf6+ (11. Nf5 $2 Nxd5 12. exd5 g6 $17 {is a bad structure for White.}) 11...
Nxf6 12. Nf3 (12. Nf5 $2 g6 13. Ne3 Nxe4 $15 {The central pawn is lost without
sufficient compensation.}) 12... Qc7 $36) 9... b5 $1 10. Kb1 (10. Nd5 $2 Qxa2
11. Bc3 Nxd5 12. exd5 Nf6 $19) 10... Qb6 $3 {The queen delivers an attack on
the knight and in the meantime finds her way to b7, a creative and very
effective placement.} 11. Be3 Qb7 12. f3 g6 $1 $132 {The success of the whole
operation is that White hasn't been able to establish the f-pawn on f4.} (12...
e6 $132 {with very good counterplay is an alternative.}) 13. Qd2 Bg7 $132 {
Black is ready for queenside play. On the other flank the h-pawn does a really
good job of stopping White's expansion.} *

