$132) 17... Ncd7 $1 {The knight on b3 obstructs the a2-bishop, so we shouldn't
exchange it We have full chances in the resulting battle, e.g.} 18. f4 (18. h5
h6 19. Bh4 Qb6 $132) 18... a5 $1 $132 (18... O-O $1 {PAP}) *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6.Bg5 Nbd7 7.f4"]
[Black "Theoretical Review"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "30"]
[EventDate "2023.10.07"]
[SourceVersionDate "2023.10.06"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. f4 (7. Qd2
$6 {The queen belongs to a light square in these lines!!... like e2 or f3!  
(PAP)} e6 $1 8. O-O-O b5 9. f3 Bb7 10. Bd3 Be7 11. h4 Rc8 $132) 7... Qa5 {
A very powerful and comparatively rare move! White has only 2 decent moves...
8.Qd3 and 8.Qd2... Black has a good chance to grab the initiative if White
goes wrong!} 8. Qd3 $1 (8. Nb3 $6 Qc7 9. Nd5 (9. Bd3 e6 (9... e5 10. O-O b5)
10. O-O b5 $132) (9. Be2 e6 10. f5 e5 (10... Be7 $3 $36 11. fxe6 fxe6 12. Nd4
Ne5 13. O-O O-O 14. Kh1 Bd7) 11. g4 $1 h6 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Qd3 b5 14. a3 Bb7
15. O-O-O Rc8 16. Kb1 Be7 {1/2-1/2 Kouskoutis,G-Santos Ruiz,M/Mamaia 2017/ CBM
180 Extra/ [,ÃéÜííçò]}) 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 h6 11. Bh4 Nf6 12. Be2 (12.
Bxf6 $2 exf6 13. Bd3 f5 14. O-O Be7 15. c3 O-O $17) 12... g6 13. O-O Bg7 14. c3
O-O 15. Bf3 a5 $132) (8. Qf3 $6 {Not so good... but everyone will play it!} h6
9. Bh4 (9. Bxf6 Nxf6 10. f5 g5 $1 {A typical positional move. Black prepares ..
.Bg7 and in the case of an en passant capture the ...Bg4 idea appears,
stopping White's long castle.} 11. fxg6 (11. O-O-O Bg7 12. g4 (12. Bc4 Bd7 13.
Bb3 Rc8 14. Rhe1 Qc5 15. Kb1 b5 $132) (12. Bd3 $6 {Too passive. The bishop
should rather go to c4.} Bd7 13. Kb1 Rc8 {Threatening ...Rxc3!} 14. Nce2 Ba4 $1
$36 {With the idea of ...Nd7 and a strong initiative.}) 12... h5 $1 {We should
break apart White's structure.} 13. gxh5 Bd7 (13... Rxh5 $36) 14. Kb1 Rc8 $15)
11... fxg6 12. Qg3 Qg5 (12... Ng4 $3 $17 13. h3 Bg7 14. O-O-O Qg5+ 15. Kb1 Qe3
16. Qxe3 Nxe3 $17) 13. Qxg5 hxg5 $15) 9... e5 $1 10. Nb3 (10. Nf5 exf4 11. Bxf6
Nxf6 12. Qxf4 Qe5 $15 {The queen trade leads to a better endgame.}) 10... Qc7
11. O-O-O (11. f5 {Too slow compared to f4-f5-e6-e5 scenarios. Here Black
played ...e5 in one go!} b5 12. a3 Bb7 $15 (12... Be7 13. O-O-O Rb8 $1 $15))
11... Be7 12. f5 b5 13. a3 Bb7 14. Bd3 (14. g4 $2 Nxe4 $3 $19 {This tactical
shot wins a pawn and possibly the game.} 15. Nxe4 Rc8 16. Bd3 Bxe4 17. Bxe4
Bxh4 $19) 14... Rc8 $132) (8. Bd3 $6 {This natural move is weak!} h6 9. Bxf6 (
9. Bh4 $6 Qb6 $3 {There is a problem of coordination in White's camp.} 10. Nb3
Qe3+ $1 {Yes, Black can go grab the f4-pawn.} 11. Qe2 Qxf4 12. Bg3 Qg5 13. O-O
e6 14. Bf4 Qh5 $17) 9... Nxf6 10. Qd2 e5 $1 {Remember, we play the active ...
e5 in most similar scenarios, not the passive e6. We now get typical Najdorf
play with the bishop pair and can be more than happy.} 11. Nb3 (11. Nf3 Be7 $15
12. O-O exf4 13. Qxf4 O-O 14. Kh1 Be6 $15) 11... Qc7 12. f5 Be7 $15 13. Qe2 b5
14. a3 Bb7 $15) (8. Qd2 $5 e6 $1 (8... h6 $5 9. Bh4 e6 $132) 9. Bc4 $6 (9. Be2
b5 10. Bf3 Bb7 11. e5 (11. f5 e5 12. Nb3 Qc7 13. a3 h6 14. Be3 Be7 $15 {
Black is simply better placed, with promising queenside chances and it's hard
for White to do something about it:} 15. O-O O-O 16. Rad1 Bc6 $3 (16... Rac8
$17) 17. Kh1 a5 $17) (11. O-O-O $2 b4 12. Nd5 exd5 13. exd5 O-O-O $17 {There's
not enough here for the piece.} 14. Nc6 (14. Nb3 Qa4) 14... Bxc6 15. dxc6 Nb6
16. Qd4 d5 $17 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Qxf6 Bd6 19. Qxf7 Bc7 $17 (19... Rhf8 $4 20.
Qb7#)) 11... Bxf3 12. exf6 (12. Nxf3 $2 b4 $17 13. exf6 (13. Ne2 Ne4) 13...
bxc3 14. bxc3 gxf6 15. Bh4 Rc8 16. O-O Qxc3 $19 {Black simply grabs material
and White has nothing to show for it.} 17. Qe2 Qc4 18. Qe1 Qxf4 19. Rd1 Be7 20.
Rd4 Qf5 21. c4 Rg8 22. Rf2 Rg4 23. h3 Rxd4 24. Nxd4 Qe5 25. Qc3 d5 26. Bg3 Rxc4
27. Qxc4 dxc4 28. Bxe5 fxe5 {0-1 Baisakow, A-Wachinger,N/ Germany 2017/EXT
2019/[ò]}) 12... gxf6 13. Nxf3 fxg5 14. Nxg5 h6 15. Nf3 Bg7 $15 {The bishop
is strong and pawns on the central files restrict White's knights. Black is
better.}) (9. Bd3 $5 Be7 10. O-O-O O-O 11. Kb1 Qc7 $132) 9... b5 $17 {The
white queen's place is on a light square, not on d2, if he wants the sacrifice
on e6 or d5 to be successful:} 10. Bxe6 (10. Bd5 exd5 11. Nc6 Qc7 12. exd5 Nb8
$3 {Immediately challenging the strong knight.} 13. Qe3+ Be7 14. Bxf6 gxf6 $15
15. O-O-O Nxc6 16. dxc6 Be6 17. Rhe1 Qa7 $3 $17 {Black steps away from the f5
threats with a tempo.} 18. Qe2 Kf8 $17) 10... fxe6 11. Nxe6 {There are a few
relatively simple ways to refute the sacrifice:} Bb7 $19 ({or} 11... b4 12. Nd5
Kf7 13. Ndc7 Ra7 14. Nd8+ Kg8 15. Nce6 Nc5 $19) 12. O-O Kf7) (8. Qe2 h6 9. Bxf6
(9. Bh4 e5 10. Nb3 Qc7 $36) 9... Nxf6 10. O-O-O Bg4 $3 11. Nf3 Rc8 $15 {
There's a big ...Rxc3 sacrifice coming!} (11... e5 $15) 12. e5 Rxc3 13. exf6
Rc7 $3 $17) 8... h6 $1 9. Bxf6 (9. Bh4 $6 Nc5 $1 10. Qd2 (10. Qe3 $2 g5 11.
fxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 Nfxe4 $19) 10... g5 $3 11. fxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 Bg7 $15 {
Black has a strong initiative for the pawn!} 13. Nb3 Nxb3 14. cxb3 Be6 {
Black will regain the pawn with benefits - b3 is hanging!} 15. Bd3 (15. Bc4
Bxc4 16. bxc4 Qc5 $17 (16... Rc8 $17) 17. O-O-O Qxc4) 15... Bxb3 $17 16. O-O
Be6) 9... Nxf6 10. f5 (10. O-O-O $1 e5 11. Nf5 Bxf5 12. exf5 Be7 $132 {The
opposite-coloured bishops position is pretty solid for both sides and
objectively around equal.}) 10... e5 $3 11. fxe6 Bxe6 $1 {We can give up the
bishop pair to speed up our development. A lot of play in the Najdorf revolves
around initiative.} 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. O-O-O Qe5 $3 {Centralization!!} 14. g3 (
14. Be2 Be7 $132 {We can easily castle both ways in the future, or even keep
the king in the centre!}) 14... Be7 15. Bh3 g5 $132 {...g4 stops White's
pressure against e6.} *

