277,277,270,270,903,1206,29995,407]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6
5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. Bc4 Qc7 $2 {Allowing the Bc4 (Bb3)-Qe2 combination!} (
7... Qb6 8. Bb3 e6 {is recommended. Black gets to play ...Nc5 and attack the
bishop in the future.}) 8. Bb3 (8. Qe2 {is also dangerous.}) 8... e6 9. O-O $1
(9. Qe2 Be7 10. Bxe6 $1 $16 {is potentially another great option for White.})
9... Nc5 $6 {Remember that allowing the structure spoiling with Bxf6 gxf6 with
the later automatic plan of f4-f5 for White is strategically usually quite bad
for Black.} (9... Be7 $2 {runs into} 10. Bxe6 $1 $18) (9... h6 10. Bh4 b5 $14 {
was still somewhat acceptable.}) 10. Bxf6 $1 gxf6 {There is plenty of really
good options for White. Black's position is simply strategically not playable.}
11. f4 $1 (11. a4 $1 Nxb3 (11... b6 12. Ba2 Bb7 13. Qh5) 12. cxb3 Bd7 (12...
Bg7 13. Re1 O-O 14. Re3) 13. Rc1 Qb6 14. Qd2 h5 15. Qd3 Bh6 16. Rc2) (11. Qh5
$1 Nxb3 12. cxb3 (12. axb3 Qc5 13. Qd1 (13. Qxc5 dxc5 14. Ndb5) (13. Nf5))
12... Qc5 $6 13. Nf5 $1 $18) 11... h5 12. f5 Be7 13. Kh1 (13. a4 Nxb3 14. cxb3
$16 {would be similar to the game.}) 13... Bd7 14. Rf3 {Black lacks an active
plan and gets completely outmaneuvered in the course of several next moves.}
