2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 7. f4 Qa5 8. Qf3 (8. Nb3
Qc7 9. Nd5 Nxd5 10. exd5 h6 11. Bh4 Nf6 12. Be2 g6 13. O-O Bg7 14. c3 O-O 15.
Bf3 a5 $132) (8. Qd2 e6 9. Bc4 $2 b5 $17 {The sacrifice on e6 tends to be
ineffective with White's queen on a dark square.} 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. Nxe6 Bb7
$19 (11... b4 12. Nd5 Kf7 13. Ndc7 Ra7 14. Nd8+ Kg8 15. Nce6 Nc5 $19) 12. O-O
Kf7 $19) 8... h6 9. Bh4 e5 $1 10. Nb3 Qc7 11. O-O-O Be7 (11... exf4 {is
possible, but I prefer the game move:} 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Qxf4 Be7 14. Kb1 O-O
15. Bd3 Be6 {I would prefer to keep the pawn on e5 in a scenario like this.
Nd4 is one unpleasant possibility.}) 12. f5 b5 13. a3 Bb7 ({In a position like
this, we should also investigate the possibility of a direct attack with} 13...
Rb8 {and ...b4.}) 14. g4 $2 ({After} 14. Bd3 {we should continue with} Rc8 {
and not a long castle!}) 14... O-O-O $2 {REMEMBER THIS IMPORTANT RULE!... WHEN
WHITE STILL HAS A DARK-SQUARED BISHOP IN THESE LINES... NEVER CASTLE LONG!!} (
14... Nxe4 $3 {is a brilliant computer suggestion that could have won the game.
} 15. Nxe4 Rc8 $1 {This intermediate move is the point.} 16. Bd3 Bxe4 17. Bxe4
Bxh4 $19 {White has nothing to show for the central pawn.}) {The rest of the
game is not really relevant, because Black's last move has worsened his
position dramatically and similar play is not recommended.} 15. Bf2 Nc5 16.
Nxc5 dxc5 17. Bg2 h5 18. h3 hxg4 19. hxg4 b4 20. axb4 cxb4 21. Nd5 Nxd5 22.
exd5 Bg5+ 23. Kb1 Rhe8 24. Qe4 Be7 25. Rh3 Qa5 26. c4 bxc3 27. Rxc3+ Kb8 28.
